\hypertarget{introduction-3}{%
\section{Introduction}\label{introduction-3}}

A function is piece of source code, separate fom the larger program,
that performs a specific task. This section of code is given a name and
can be called from the main program. It is called by using its given
name.

Functions are the \textbf{verbs} of a programming language. They signify
action, and take subjects and objects (as it were).

Functions take \textbf{input} and produce \textbf{output}.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Function inputs are called both \textbf{parameters} and
  \textbf{arguments}.
\item
  Outputs are called \textbf{return} values
\end{itemize}

Functions are always written with parentheses at the end of their names,
e.g.

\texttt{len(some\_list)}

Internally, they contain a block of code to do their work.

Often the producte a \textbf{transformation} \ldots{} from simple to
complex.

When you use a function, we say you \textbf{call} a function.
Programmers speak of ``function calls'' and ``callbacks''.

\hypertarget{benefits}{%
\section{Benefits}\label{benefits}}

Reduce complex tasks into simpler tasks.

Eliminate duplicate code -- no need to re-write, reuse function as
needed.

Code reuse. Once function is written, you can reuse it in any other
program.

Distribute tasks to multiple programmers. For example, each function can
be written by someone.

Hide implementation details, i.e.~abstraction.

Increase code readability.

Improve debugging by improving traceability. Things are easier to
follow; you can jump from function to function.

\hypertarget{built-in-functions}{%
\section{Built-in Functions}\label{built-in-functions}}

Python provides many \textbf{built-in} functions. See
\href{https://docs.python.org/3/library/functions.html}{Python built-in
functions}.

We've looked at many of these already.

These are functions that are available to use any time your are running
Python.

To take one simple example, this is a built-in function:
\texttt{bool()}.

Takes an argument \(x\) and returns a boolean value, i.e.~\texttt{True}
or \texttt{False}.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\BuiltInTok{bool}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{), }\BuiltInTok{bool}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{500}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{imported-functions}{%
\section{Imported Functions}\label{imported-functions}}

Python is meant to be a highly modular language.\\
It is not designed to have a lot of special purpose functions built into
it.\\
These keeps it light and highly customizable.

Many functions (and other stuff) can be imported into a program to add
to the functions that you can call in a script.

There are also many \textbf{packages} to bring in additional functions.

Packages and Libraries

\hypertarget{user-defined-functions}{%
\section{User-Defined Functions}\label{user-defined-functions}}

Python makes it easy for you to write your own functions. These are
called \textbf{user-defined} functions.

Let's write a function to compare the list against a threshold.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ vals\_greater\_than\_or\_equal\_to\_threshold(vals, thresh):}
    \CommentTok{\textquotesingle{}\textquotesingle{}\textquotesingle{}}
\CommentTok{    This is the "docstring" of a function. It is optional but expected. It describes it\textquotesingle{}s }
\CommentTok{    purpose and the nature of the input and return values, as well as a sense of what it does.}
\CommentTok{    More elaborate information should appear in external documentation packages with the function.}
\CommentTok{    }
\CommentTok{    PURPOSE: Given a list of values, compare each value against a threshold}
\CommentTok{    }
\CommentTok{    INPUTS}
\CommentTok{    vals    list of ints or floats}
\CommentTok{    thresh  int or float}
\CommentTok{    }
\CommentTok{    OUTPUT}
\CommentTok{    bools  list of booleans}
\CommentTok{    \textquotesingle{}\textquotesingle{}\textquotesingle{}}
    
\NormalTok{    bools }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ [val }\OperatorTok{\textgreater{}=}\NormalTok{ thresh }\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ val }\KeywordTok{in}\NormalTok{ vals]}
    
    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ bools}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Let's break down the components}

The function definition starts with \texttt{def}, followed by name, one
or more arguments in parenthesis, and then a colon.

Next comes a \textbf{docstring} to provide information to users about
how and why to use the function.

The function \textbf{body} follows.

:astly is a \texttt{return} statement

The \textbf{function call} allows for the function to be used.\\
It consists of function name and required arguments:

\texttt{vals\_greater\_than\_or\_equal\_to\_threshold(arg1,\ arg2)}
where \texttt{arg1}, \texttt{arg2} are arbitrary names.

\hypertarget{about-the-docstring}{%
\subsection{About the docstring}\label{about-the-docstring}}

A \textbf{docstring} m occurs as first statement in module, function,
class, or method definition

Internally, it is saved in \texttt{\_\_doc\_\_} attribute of the
function object.

It needs to be indented.

It can be a single line or a multi-line string.

\hypertarget{lets-test-our-function}{%
\subsection{Let's test our function}\label{lets-test-our-function}}

The function body used a \texttt{list\ comprehension} for the compare:

\texttt{{[}val\ \textgreater{}=\ thresh\ for\ val\ in\ vals{]}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\# validate that it works for ints}

\NormalTok{x }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ [}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{thr }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{4}

\NormalTok{vals\_greater\_than\_or\_equal\_to\_threshold(x, thr)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\# validate that it works for floats}

\NormalTok{x }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ [}\FloatTok{3.0}\NormalTok{, }\FloatTok{4.2}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{thr }\OperatorTok{=} \FloatTok{4.2}

\NormalTok{vals\_greater\_than\_or\_equal\_to\_threshold(x, thr)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\# vals\_greater\_than\_or\_equal\_to\_threshold("foo", "bar")}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

This gives correct results and does exactly what we want.

\hypertarget{users-can-print-the-docstring}{%
\subsection{Users can print the
docstring}\label{users-can-print-the-docstring}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(vals\_greater\_than\_or\_equal\_to\_threshold.\_\_doc\_\_)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

print the help

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\BuiltInTok{help}\NormalTok{(vals\_greater\_than\_or\_equal\_to\_threshold)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{?vals\_greater\_than\_or\_equal\_to\_threshold}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Let's test our function}

The function body used a \texttt{list\ comprehension} for the
comparison:

\texttt{{[}val\ \textgreater{}=\ thresh\ for\ val\ in\ vals{]}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\# validate that it works for ints}

\NormalTok{x }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ [}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{thr }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{4}

\NormalTok{vals\_greater\_than\_or\_equal\_to\_threshold(x, thr)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\# validate that it works for floats}

\NormalTok{x }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ [}\FloatTok{3.0}\NormalTok{, }\FloatTok{4.2}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{thr }\OperatorTok{=} \FloatTok{4.2}

\NormalTok{vals\_greater\_than\_or\_equal\_to\_threshold(x, thr)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

This gives correct results and does exactly what we want.

Print the docstring

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(vals\_greater\_than\_or\_equal\_to\_threshold.\_\_doc\_\_)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Print the help

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\BuiltInTok{help}\NormalTok{(vals\_greater\_than\_or\_equal\_to\_threshold)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Use the \texttt{?} prefix \ldots{}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{?vals\_greater\_than\_or\_equal\_to\_threshold}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{passing-parameters}{%
\section{Passing Parameters}\label{passing-parameters}}

Functions need to be called with correct number of parameters.

This function requires two params, but the function call includes only
one param.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ fcn\_bad\_args(x, y):}
    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ x }\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{ y}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{fcn\_bad\_args(}\DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{parameter-order}{%
\subsection{Parameter Order}\label{parameter-order}}

When calling a function, \textbf{parameter order matters}.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ fcn\_swapped\_args(x, y):}
\NormalTok{    out }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{5} \OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{ x }\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{ y}
    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ out}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{x }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{1}
\NormalTok{y }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{2}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{fcn\_swapped\_args(x, y)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{fcn\_swapped\_args(y, x)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Generally it's best to keep parameters in order.

You can swap the order by putting the parameter names in the function
call.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{fcn\_swapped\_args(y}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{y, x}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{x)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{weirdness-alert}{%
\subsection{Weirdness Alert}\label{weirdness-alert}}

Note that the same name can be used for the parameter names and the
variables passed to them.

The names themselves have nothng to do with each other!

In other words, just because a function names an argument
\texttt{foo},\\
the variables passed to it don't have to name \texttt{foo} or anything
like it.\\
They can even be named the same thing -- it does not matter.

\hypertarget{unpacking-list-likes-with-args}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{Unpacking List-likes with
\texttt{*args}}{Unpacking List-likes with *args}}\label{unpacking-list-likes-with-args}}

The \texttt{*} prefix operator can be passed to avoid specifying the
arguments individually.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ show\_arg\_expansion(}\OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{models):}
    
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"models          :"}\NormalTok{, models)}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"input arg type  :"}\NormalTok{,  }\BuiltInTok{type}\NormalTok{(models))}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"input arg length:"}\NormalTok{, }\BuiltInTok{len}\NormalTok{(models))}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}{-}"}\NormalTok{)}
    
    \ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ mod }\KeywordTok{in}\NormalTok{ models:}
        \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(mod)    }
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

We can pass a tuple of values to the function \ldots{}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{show\_arg\_expansion(}\StringTok{"logreg"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"naive\_bayes"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"gbm"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

You can also pass a list to the function.

If you want the elements unpacked, put \texttt{*} before the list.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{models }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ [}\StringTok{"logreg"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"naive\_bayes"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"gbm"}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{show\_arg\_expansion(}\OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{models)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

This approach allows your function to accept an arbitrary number of
arguments.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{show\_arg\_expansion(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}a b c d e f g\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{.split())}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{The reverse is true, too.}

You can use the \texttt{*} prefix to pass list-like objects to a
function that specifies its arguments.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ arg\_expansion\_example(x, y):}
    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ x}\OperatorTok{**}\NormalTok{y}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{my\_args }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ [}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{8}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{arg\_expansion\_example(}\OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{my\_args)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

But, the passed object must be the right length.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{my\_args2 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ [}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{8}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{arg\_expansion\_example(}\OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{my\_args2)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\# **my\_dict}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{default-arguments}{%
\section{Default Arguments}\label{default-arguments}}

Use default arguments to set the value of arguments when left
unspecified.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ show\_results(precision, printing}\OperatorTok{=}\VariableTok{True}\NormalTok{):}
\NormalTok{    precision }\OperatorTok{=} \BuiltInTok{round}\NormalTok{(precision, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}
    \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ printing:}
      \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}precision =\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, precision)}
    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ precision}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{pr }\OperatorTok{=} \FloatTok{0.912}
\NormalTok{res }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ show\_results(pr)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

The function call didn't specify \texttt{printing}, so it defaulted to
True.

\textbf{NOTE:} Default arguments must follow non-default arguments. This
causes trouble:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ show\_results(precision, printing}\OperatorTok{=}\VariableTok{True}\NormalTok{, uhoh):}
\NormalTok{    precision }\OperatorTok{=} \BuiltInTok{round}\NormalTok{(precision, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}
    \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ printing:}
      \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}precision =\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, precision)}
    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ precision}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{returning-values}{%
\section{Returning Values}\label{returning-values}}

Functions are not required to have return statement.

If there is no return statement, a function returns \texttt{None}.

Functions can return no value (\texttt{None}), one value, or many.

Many values are returned as a tuple.

Any Python object can be returned.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\# returns None, and prints.}

\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ fcn\_nothing\_to\_return(x, y):}
\NormalTok{    out }\OperatorTok{=} \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}nothing to see here!\textquotesingle{}}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(out)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{fcn\_nothing\_to\_return(x, y)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{r }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ fcn\_nothing\_to\_return(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(r)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\# returns three values}

\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ negate\_coords(x, y, z):}
    \ControlFlowTok{return} \OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{x, }\OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{y, }\OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{z }
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{a, b, c }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ negate\_coords(}\DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{20}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{30}\NormalTok{)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}a =\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, a)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}b =\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, b)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}c =\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, c)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{If you don't need an output, use the dummy variable \texttt{\_}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{d, e, \_ }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ negate\_coords(}\DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{20}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{30}\NormalTok{)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}d =\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, d)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}e =\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, e)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Note:} It's generally a good idea to include return statements,
even if not returning a value.

This shows that you did not forget to consider the return value.

You can use \texttt{return} or \texttt{return\ None}.

\textbf{Functions can contain multiple return statements}.

These may be used under different logical conditions.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ absolute\_value(num):}
    \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ num }\OperatorTok{\textgreater{}=} \DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{:}
        \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ num}
    \ControlFlowTok{return} \OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{num}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{absolute\_value(}\OperatorTok{{-}}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{absolute\_value(}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

For non-negative values, the first \texttt{return} is reached.\\
For negative values, the second \texttt{return} is reached.

\hypertarget{function-design}{%
\section{Function Design}\label{function-design}}

A function is not just a bag of code!

Some good practices for creating and using functions:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  design a function to do one thing
\end{itemize}

Make them as simple as possible, which makes them:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  more comprehensible
\item
  easier to maintain
\item
  reusable
\end{itemize}

This helps avoid situations where a team has 20 variations of similar
functions.

Give your function a good name.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  It should reflect the action it performs.
\item
  Be consistent in your naming conventions.
\item
  A name like \texttt{compute\_variances\_sort\_save\_print} suggests
  the function is overworked!
\end{itemize}

If the function \texttt{compute\_variances} also produces plots and
updates variables, it will cause confusion.

Always give your function a docstring - Particularly important since
indicating data types is not required.\\
- As a side note, you can include this information by using \textbf{type
annotation}.

Finally, at some point you may be interested to learn some of the
formatting languages that have been developed to write docstrings. See
\href{https://learning.oreilly.com/library/view/learning-python-5th/9781449355722/ch15.html}{Lutz
2019} and this web page about
\href{https://realpython.com/documenting-python-code/}{Documenting
Python Code} for more info.

\hypertarget{nb-lambda-functions}{%
\chapter{NB: Lambda Functions}\label{nb-lambda-functions}}

\hypertarget{introduction-4}{%
\section{Introduction}\label{introduction-4}}

Python lambda functions are small, informal functions. They don't get a
name.

The are ``anonymous.''

From Lutz 2019:

\begin{quote}
Besides the \texttt{def} statement, Python also provides an expression
form that generates function objects. Because of its similarity to a
tool in the Lisp language, it's called lambda. Like \texttt{def}, this
expression creates a function to be called later, but it returns the
function instead of assigning it to a name. This is why lambdas are
sometimes known as anonymous (i.e., unnamed) functions. In practice,
they are often used as a way to inline a function definition, or to
defer execution of a piece of code.
\end{quote}

The general form of a lambda function is:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ x: x}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
<function __main__.<lambda>(x)>
\end{verbatim}

You can call the function like this:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ x: x)(}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
2
\end{verbatim}

\textbf{increment x}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ x: x}\OperatorTok{+}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)(}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
6
\end{verbatim}

\textbf{sum two variables}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ x, y: x }\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{ y}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
<function __main__.<lambda>(x, y)>
\end{verbatim}

\hypertarget{assigned-to-a-variable}{%
\section{Assigned to a Variable}\label{assigned-to-a-variable}}

Even though they don't get a name, they can be assigned to variables.

Here, a lambda function gets assigned to \texttt{sum\_two\_vars}.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{sum\_two\_vars }\OperatorTok{=} \KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ x, y: x }\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{ y}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{sum\_two\_vars(}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Check if a value is non-negative}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{is\_non\_negative }\OperatorTok{=} \KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ x: x }\OperatorTok{\textgreater{}=} \DecValTok{0}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{is\_non\_negative(}\OperatorTok{{-}}\DecValTok{9}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{is\_non\_negative(}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Package first element and all data into tuple}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{pack\_first\_all }\OperatorTok{=} \KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ x: (x[}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{], x)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{casado }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ (}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}rice\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{,}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}beans\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{,}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}salad\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{,}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}plaintain\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{,}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}chicken\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{) }\CommentTok{\# a typical Costa Rican dish}

\NormalTok{pack\_first\_all(casado)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Check for keyword ``dirty''}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{is\_dirty }\OperatorTok{=} \KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ txt: }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}dirty\textquotesingle{}} \KeywordTok{in}\NormalTok{ txt}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{kitchen\_inspection }\OperatorTok{=} \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}dirty dishes\textquotesingle{}}
\NormalTok{is\_dirty(kitchen\_inspection)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{kitchen\_inspection }\OperatorTok{=} \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}pretty clean!\textquotesingle{}}
\NormalTok{is\_dirty(kitchen\_inspection)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

**pass *args for unspecified number of arguments**

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{lambda} \OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{args: }\BuiltInTok{sum}\NormalTok{(args))(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{using-lambda}{%
\section{Using Lambda}\label{using-lambda}}

Lambda functions are often used in Pandas. We will discuss there use in
more detail when we get to that topic.

\hypertarget{nb-recursion}{%
\chapter{NB: Recursion}\label{nb-recursion}}

\textbf{Concepts} - recursion - recursive function - stack - stack
overflow

\hypertarget{introduction-5}{%
\section{Introduction}\label{introduction-5}}

A recursive function is \textbf{a function that calls itself}.

This is weird, since it does not seem possible. How can a definition
refer to itself?

In philosophy, this is expressed in the Barber's Paradox:

\begin{quote}
The barber is the one who shaves all those, and those only, who do not
shave themselves. Does the barber shave himself?
\end{quote}

Formally, it is a type of
\href{https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Self-reference}{self-reference},
like \texttt{This\ sentence\ is\ false.}

\textbf{A Cute Definition}

\textbf{recursion} - the art of defining something (at least partly) in
terms of itself, which is a naughty no-no in dictionaries but often
works out okay in computer programs if you're careful not to recurse
forever (which is like an infinite loop with more spectacular failure
modes).

Source: \emph{PerlDoc}

\hypertarget{a-formal-definition}{%
\subsection{A Formal Definition}\label{a-formal-definition}}

In mathematics and computer science, a class of objects or methods
exhibits \emph{recursive behavior} when it can be defined by two
properties:

A \textbf{simple base} case (or cases): a terminating scenario that does
not use recursion to produce an answer.

A \textbf{recursive step}: a set of rules that reduces all successive
cases toward the base case.

\hypertarget{as-seen-in-nature}{%
\subsection{As Seen in Nature}\label{as-seen-in-nature}}

Recursion occurs naturally when a process applies a rule to itself
successively.

We see this in fractals.

\hypertarget{infinite-loops-and-stack-overflows}{%
\subsection{Infinite Loops and Stack
Overflows}\label{infinite-loops-and-stack-overflows}}

Every recursive function must have a base condition that stops the
recursion or else the function calls itself infinitely.

The Python interpreter limits the depths of recursion to help avoid
infinite recursions, resulting in stack overflows.

The \textbf{call stack} is where information is stored relating to the
active subroutines in a program.

The call stack has a limited amount of available memory. When excessive
memory consumption occurs on the call stack, it results in a
\textbf{stack overflow error}.

\hypertarget{a-note-of-caution}{%
\subsection{A Note of Caution}\label{a-note-of-caution}}

So, Recursion is cool, but is expensive and complicated.

Recursive functions can usually be implemented by traditional loops.

\hypertarget{example-computing-factorials}{%
\section{Example: Computing
Factorials}\label{example-computing-factorials}}

\href{https://www.programiz.com/python-programming/recursion}{Source}

The factorial of a number \(n\) is the product of all the integers from
\(1\) to \(n\).

For example, the factorial of \(5\) (denoted as \(5!\)) is
\(1\times2\times3\times4\times5 = 120\).

Let's implement this in code using a recursive function.

\hypertarget{recursive-function}{%
\subsection{Recursive Function}\label{recursive-function}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{n }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{5}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\#| tags: []}
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ factorial(x):}
    \CommentTok{"Finds the factorial of an integer using recursion"}
    \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ x }\OperatorTok{==} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{: }\CommentTok{\# Base condition}
        \ControlFlowTok{return} \DecValTok{1}
    \ControlFlowTok{else}\NormalTok{:}
        \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ x }\OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{ factorial(x}\OperatorTok{{-}}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\#| tags: []}
\OperatorTok{\%}\NormalTok{time factorial(n)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{as-a-while-loop}{%
\subsection{As a while loop}\label{as-a-while-loop}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ factorial\_while(x):}
    \CommentTok{"Finds the factorial of an integer using a while loop"}
\NormalTok{    f }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ x}
    \ControlFlowTok{while}\NormalTok{ x }\OperatorTok{\textgreater{}} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{:}
\NormalTok{        x }\OperatorTok{{-}=} \DecValTok{1}
\NormalTok{        f }\OperatorTok{*=}\NormalTok{ x}
    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ f}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\OperatorTok{\%}\NormalTok{time factorial\_while(n)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{as-a-for-loop}{%
\subsection{As a for loop}\label{as-a-for-loop}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ factorial\_for(x):}
    \CommentTok{"Finds the factorial of an integer using a for loop"}
\NormalTok{    f }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ x}
    \ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ i }\KeywordTok{in} \BuiltInTok{range}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, x):}
\NormalTok{        x }\OperatorTok{{-}=} \DecValTok{1}
\NormalTok{        f }\OperatorTok{*=}\NormalTok{ x}
    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ f}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\OperatorTok{\%}\NormalTok{time factorial\_for(n)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{compare-functions-as-n-increases}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Compare functions as \(n\)
increases}{Compare functions as n increases}}\label{compare-functions-as-n-increases}}

\hypertarget{increase-n-to-50}{%
\subsubsection{Increase n to 50}\label{increase-n-to-50}}

\hypertarget{example-the-fibonacci-sequence}{%
\section{Example: The Fibonacci
sequence}\label{example-the-fibonacci-sequence}}

Fib(0) = 0 (base case 1)

Fib(1) = 1 (base case 2)

For all integers n \textgreater{} 1, Fib(n) = Fib(n − 1) + Fib(n − 2)

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ Fibonacci(n):}
    \CommentTok{"Compute a Fibonacci Sequence using recursion"}

    \CommentTok{\# If n is negative}
    \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ n }\OperatorTok{\textless{}} \DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{:}
        \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Incorrect input. Value must be 0 or greater."}\NormalTok{)}

    \CommentTok{\# If n is 0}
    \ControlFlowTok{elif}\NormalTok{ n }\OperatorTok{==} \DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{:}
        \ControlFlowTok{return} \DecValTok{0}

    \CommentTok{\# If n is 1 or 2}
    \ControlFlowTok{elif}\NormalTok{ n }\OperatorTok{==} \DecValTok{1} \KeywordTok{or}\NormalTok{ n }\OperatorTok{==} \DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{:}
        \ControlFlowTok{return} \DecValTok{1}

    \ControlFlowTok{else}\NormalTok{:}
        \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ Fibonacci(n }\OperatorTok{{-}} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{ Fibonacci(n }\OperatorTok{{-}} \DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{n }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{9}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{Fibonacci(}\DecValTok{9}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ n }\KeywordTok{in} \BuiltInTok{range}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{100}\NormalTok{):}
    \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ n }\OperatorTok{\textgreater{}} \DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{: }\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{", "}\NormalTok{, end}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{""}\NormalTok{)}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(Fibonacci(n), end}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{""}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{as-a-for-loop-1}{%
\subsection{As a for loop}\label{as-a-for-loop-1}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ fibber(r:}\BuiltInTok{int} \OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{):}
    \CommentTok{"""}
\CommentTok{    Computes a Fibonacci Sequence using a for loop. }
\CommentTok{    Parameter r must be in integer \textgreater{} 3. Defaults to 10.}
\CommentTok{    Returns a string as a comma{-}limited series.}
\CommentTok{    """}
\NormalTok{    seq }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ [}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{] }
\NormalTok{    kernel }\OperatorTok{=} \KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ x, i: x[i}\OperatorTok{{-}}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{] }\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{ x[i}\OperatorTok{{-}}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{]}
    \ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ n }\KeywordTok{in} \BuiltInTok{range}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, r):}
\NormalTok{        seq.append(seq[n}\OperatorTok{{-}}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{] }\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{ seq[n}\OperatorTok{{-}}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{])}
    \ControlFlowTok{return} \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}, \textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{.join([}\BuiltInTok{str}\NormalTok{(x) }\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ x }\KeywordTok{in}\NormalTok{ seq])}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{fibber(}\DecValTok{20}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{aside-a-general-sequence-function}{%
\section{Aside: A General Sequence
Function}\label{aside-a-general-sequence-function}}

Recursive functions are often used to produce mathematical sequences,
but since they have limits on depth, they are of limited use for this
purpose.

Here is a function that can combine many sequences using two sequence
parameters: * The initial state of the sequence, represented as the list
\texttt{seq}. * For example, in the Fibonacci sequence, seq is
\texttt{{[}1,\ 1,\ 2{]}} * The function to apply to the sequence at each
iteration, represneted as a \texttt{lambda} function with the arguments
\texttt{x} and \texttt{i} for the the sequence list \texttt{seq} and the
iteration number respectively. * For example, in the Fibonacci sequence
the kernel function is
\texttt{lambda\ x,\ i:\ x{[}i-1{]}\ +\ x{[}i-2{]}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\#| tags: []}
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ sequencer(n:}\BuiltInTok{int} \OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{, seq}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{], kernel}\OperatorTok{=}\KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ x, i: x[i}\OperatorTok{{-}}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{] }\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{ x[i}\OperatorTok{{-}}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{]):}
    \CommentTok{"""}
\CommentTok{    Computes a Sequence using a for loop. }
\CommentTok{    }
\CommentTok{    Parameter n in integer which must be \textgreater{} 3. Defaults to 10.}
\CommentTok{    Parameter seq is as list in the initial state of the sequence. Must have at least one value. Defaults to Fibonacci [1,1,2]}
\CommentTok{    Parameter kernel is the kernel function applied to the series at each iteration. x stands for the seq list, i to the iteration number. Defaults to lambda x, i: x[i{-}1] + x[i{-}2]}
\CommentTok{    }
\CommentTok{    Returns a string as a comma{-}limited series.}
\CommentTok{    """}
    
    \ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ i }\KeywordTok{in} \BuiltInTok{range}\NormalTok{(}\BuiltInTok{len}\NormalTok{(seq), n): seq.append(kernel(seq, i))}
    \ControlFlowTok{return} \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}, \textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{.join([}\BuiltInTok{str}\NormalTok{(x) }\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ x }\KeywordTok{in}\NormalTok{ seq])}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{n }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{8}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\OperatorTok{\%}\NormalTok{time sequencer(n, [}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{], }\KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ x, i: i)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{The series of positive integers}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{sequencer(n, [}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{], }\KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ x, i: x[i}\OperatorTok{{-}}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{] }\OperatorTok{+} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{The series of even numbers}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{sequencer(n, [}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{], }\KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ x, i: x[i}\OperatorTok{{-}}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{] }\OperatorTok{+} \DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{The series of odd numbers}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{sequencer(n, [}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{], }\KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ x, i: x[i}\OperatorTok{{-}}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{] }\OperatorTok{+} \DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{The series of Fibonacci numbers}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{sequencer(n, [}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{], }\KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ x, i: x[i}\OperatorTok{{-}}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{] }\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{ x[i}\OperatorTok{{-}}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{])}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{The series of Squares}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{sequencer(n, [}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{], }\KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ x, i: x[i}\OperatorTok{{-}}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{]}\OperatorTok{**}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{nb-variable-scope}{%
\chapter{NB: Variable Scope}\label{nb-variable-scope}}

\hypertarget{overview-1}{%
\section{Overview}\label{overview-1}}

A variable's \textbf{scope} is the part of a program where it is
\textbf{visible}.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Scope refers to the \textbf{coding region}, such as a function block,
  from which a particular Python object is accessible.
\item
  Visible means available or \textbf{usable} to the code block in
  question.
\item
  If a variable is \textbf{in scope} to a function, it is visible the
  function.
\item
  If it is \textbf{out of scope} to a function, it is not visible the
  function.
\end{itemize}

When a variable is defined \textbf{inside} of a function, is is not
visible outside of the function. * We say such variables are
\textbf{local} to the function. * They are also removed from memory when
the function completes.

When a variable is defined \textbf{outside} of any function in a script,
it is visible to any function inside of the script * We say such
variables are \textbf{global} to the functions in the file or context in
which the variables are defined. * A function can replace a global
variable with local variable by defining that variable. In this case, a
variable can have global and local versions in the same program.

Sometimes variable scope is called \textbf{lexical} scope.

It is helpful to have a good understanding of scope to avoid surprises
and confusion.

The concept is easier than it may look in the abstract. Let's look at
some examples where we vary the use of local and global definitions of
\texttt{x}.

\hypertarget{lutz-on-scoping}{%
\section{Lutz on Scoping}\label{lutz-on-scoping}}

Here's an excerpt from
\href{https://learning.oreilly.com/library/view/learning-python-5th/9781449355722/ch17.html\#scope_details}{Lutz,
Chapter 17}. Please read the whole thing.

\textbf{The enclosing module is a global scope.} Each module is a global
scope---that is, a namespace in which variables created (assigned) at
the top level of the module file live. Global variables become
attributes of a module object to the outside world after imports but can
also be used as simple variables within the module file itself.

\textbf{The global scope spans a single file only.} Don't be fooled by
the word ``global'' here---names at the top level of a file are global
to code within that single file only. There is really no notion of a
single, all-encompassing global file-based scope in Python. Instead,
names are partitioned into modules, and you must always import a module
explicitly if you want to be able to use the names its file defines.
\textbf{When you hear ``global'' in Python, think ``module.''}

\textbf{Assigned names are local unless declared global or nonlocal.} By
default, all the names assigned inside a function definition are put in
the local scope (the namespace associated with the function call). If
you need to assign a name that lives at the top level of the module
enclosing the function, you can do so by declaring it in a global
statement inside the function. If you need to assign a name that lives
in an enclosing def, as of Python 3.X you can do so by declaring it in a
nonlocal statement.

\textbf{All other names are enclosing function locals, globals, or
built-ins.} Names not assigned a value in the function definition are
assumed to be enclosing scope locals, defined in a physically
surrounding def statement; globals that live in the enclosing module's
namespace; or built-ins in the predefined built-ins module Python
provides.

\textbf{Each call to a function creates a new local scope.} Every time
you call a function, you create a new local scope---that is, a namespace
in which the names created inside that function will usually live. You
can think of each def statement (and lambda expression) as defining a
new local scope, but the local scope actually corresponds to a function
call. Because Python allows functions to call themselves to loop---an
advanced technique known as recursion and noted briefly in Chapter~9
when we explored comparisons---each active call receives its own copy of
the function's local variables. Recursion is useful in functions we
write as well, to process structures whose shapes can't be predicted
ahead of time; we'll explore it more fully in Chapter~19.

And here is a nice visualization of scopes:

\begin{figure}

{\centering \includegraphics{notebooks/M04_PythonFunctions/assets/lp5e_1701.png}

}

\caption{Car with tinted glass}

\end{figure}

Please read
\href{https://learning.oreilly.com/library/view/learning-python-5th/9781449355722/ch17.html\#scope_details}{Lutz,
Chapter 17} for a good overview of scoping.

\hypertarget{the-tinted-glass-metaphor}{%
\section{The Tinted Glass Metaphor}\label{the-tinted-glass-metaphor}}

So, code regions within a program are like vehicles with tinted glass: *
Passengers can see outside, but outsiders can't see inside. * Passengers
in a vehicle can let outsiders look in by lowering the window.

Or something. Lile models, all metaphors are wrong, but some are useful.
:-)

\hypertarget{example-1}{%
\section{Example 1}\label{example-1}}

\textbf{\texttt{x} defined outside a function but used inside of it}

In the code below: * \texttt{x} is \textbf{global} and seen from inside
the function.\\
* \texttt{a} is \textbf{local} to the function. trying to print outside
function throws error.

Note that arguments are essentially locally defined variables.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{x }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{10}

\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ scope\_func1(a):}
\NormalTok{    out }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ x }\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{ a}
    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ out}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

The following works because \texttt{x} is global and functions can
access globals so long as they don't reassign the variable name.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{y }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ scope\_func1(}\DecValTok{6}\NormalTok{)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(y)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

The following fails because \texttt{a} local and not visible outside the
function.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(a)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{example-2}{%
\section{Example 2}\label{example-2}}

\textbf{\texttt{x} defined both outside and inside function, and used
inside the function}

This function reassigns \texttt{x}, so it becomes local.

Note that a variable becomes local once it is used in an assignment
statement within a function, or if it the name of an argument.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{x }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{10} \CommentTok{\# Global}

\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ scope\_func2(a):}

\NormalTok{    x }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{20} \CommentTok{\# Local}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}x from inside:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, x)}
    
\NormalTok{    out }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ x }\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{ a}
    
    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ out}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{y }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ scope\_func2(}\DecValTok{6}\NormalTok{)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(y)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}x from outside:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, x)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{example-2a}{%
\section{Example 2a}\label{example-2a}}

Here we define \texttt{x} as an argument.

This has the same effect as defining it in the body of the function.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{x }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{10} \CommentTok{\# Global}

\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ scope\_func2a(a, x}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{20}\NormalTok{): }\CommentTok{\# Argment variables are local}

    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}x from inside:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, x)}
    
\NormalTok{    out }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ x }\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{ a}
    
    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ out}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}x from outside before function:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, x)}
\NormalTok{y }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ scope\_func2a(}\DecValTok{6}\NormalTok{)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(y)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}x from outside before function:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, x)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

As an argument, though, it can be assigned the value of the global.

Nevertheless, only the value is being passed between the global and
local versions of \texttt{x}.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{x }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{10} \CommentTok{\# Global}

\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ scope\_func2a(a, x}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{20}\NormalTok{):}

    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}x from inside before incremenet:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, x)}
\NormalTok{    x }\OperatorTok{+=} \DecValTok{10}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}x from inside after incremenet:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, x)}
    
\NormalTok{    out }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ x }\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{ a}
    
    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ out}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}x from outside before function:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, x)}
\NormalTok{y }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ scope\_func2a(}\DecValTok{6}\NormalTok{, x)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(y)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}x from outside after function:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, x)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{example-3}{%
\section{Example 3}\label{example-3}}

\textbf{\texttt{x} defined both outside and inside function, and used
inside the function in both global and local modes}

This one is interesting. It fails, but it's not clear why at first.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{x }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{10}

\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ scope\_func3(a):}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}x from fcn, before local definition:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, x) }\CommentTok{\# Global use of x}
\NormalTok{    x }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{20} \CommentTok{\# Local use of x}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}x from fcn, after local definition:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, x)}
\NormalTok{    out }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ x }\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{ a}
    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ out}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}x from outside before local definition:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, x)}
\NormalTok{scope\_func3(}\DecValTok{6}\NormalTok{)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}x from outside after local definition:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, x)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

The error can be fixed by referencing x as \texttt{global} inside
function.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{x }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{10}

\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ scope\_func4(a):}
    \KeywordTok{global}\NormalTok{ x}
    
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}x from inside, before local definition:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, x)}
\NormalTok{    x }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{20}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}x from inside, after local definition:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, x)}
    
\NormalTok{    out }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ x }\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{ a}
    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ out}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}x from outside, before local definition:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, x)}
\NormalTok{y }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ scope\_func4(}\DecValTok{6}\NormalTok{)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(y)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}x from outside, after local definition:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, x)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Note that the two instances of the variable \texttt{z} coexist in the
same script because of the rules of scoping.

\hypertarget{local-global-conflicts}{%
\section{Local / global conflicts}\label{local-global-conflicts}}

What will calling \texttt{guess()} do?

Hint: ``If you assign a name in any way within a def, it will become a
local to that function by default.'' (Lutz)

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{x }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{10}

\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ guess():}
\NormalTok{    x }\OperatorTok{+=} \DecValTok{10} 
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(x)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{guess()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Consider the following expression, which is the same as the unary
operation inside of the function \texttt{guess()}.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{x }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ x }\OperatorTok{+} \DecValTok{10}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

The \texttt{x} on the left is \texttt{local}, since it is being
\emph{defined} inside the function.

However, the \texttt{x} on the right is assumed to already be defined,
and so is \texttt{global}.

In effect, Python is presented with a contradiction and so throws an
error.

We will see that R does not do this; it just goes with the
\texttt{global}.

\hypertarget{nonlocal}{%
\section{Nonlocal}\label{nonlocal}}

If a variable is assigned in an enclosing \texttt{def}, it is
\texttt{nonlocal} to nested functions.

The \texttt{nonlocal} keyword is similar to \texttt{global}, except that
it refers to the scope of the enclosing function, not the script that
contains the funtions.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{x }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{10} \CommentTok{\# Global}
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ func1(): }\CommentTok{\# Enclosing function}
\NormalTok{    x }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{20} \CommentTok{\# Local to function; "Nonlocal" to nested function}
    \KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ func1a():}
\NormalTok{        x }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{30} \CommentTok{\# Local to nested function}

\hypertarget{namespaces}{%
\section{Namespaces}\label{namespaces}}

Definitions of scope make reference to \textbf{namespaces}. Scope and
namespaces are closely intertwined concepts. Sometimes it is assumed
that the reader knows what this means.

If you've never heard of namespaces, or are unsure of what they are,
here's a brief explanation.

A namespace is a system that allows for \textbf{a unique name} to
associated with each and \textbf{every object} in a Python program. *
Remember that \textbf{an object can be anything} in Python, not just
variable, e.g.~a function or a class. * Python maintains namespaces
internally as \textbf{dictionaries}.

A good \textbf{analogy} to a namespace system is the \textbf{file
system} on a computer. You can have files of the same name so long as
they are in different folders. The complete name of the file is actually
the filename and the names of its parent folders, i.e.~the path to the
file in the file system.

Another anology is in \textbf{human names} -- personal names and family
names, i.e.~first and last names in European countries. These in turn
might be contained by larger social groupings.

Finally, another analogy is \textbf{home addresses} -- house numbers and
street names can be reused based on their ``path'' in the tree of
geographic entities that include cities, states, nations, etc.

Similarly, Python understands what exact method or variable one is
trying to point to in the code, depending upon the namespace.

Note that in each of these cases, \textbf{the data structure is a
directed acyclic graph (DAG)}, which is universal structure for
organizing unique names.

\hypertarget{some-visualizations}{%
\section{Some Visualizations}\label{some-visualizations}}

The same object name can be present in multiple namespaces as isolation
between the same name is maintained by their namespace.

Source:
\href{https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/namespaces-and-scope-in-python/}{``Namespaces
and Scope in Python'' (GFG)}.

\hypertarget{nb-functions-calling-functions}{%
\chapter{NB: Functions Calling
Functions}\label{nb-functions-calling-functions}}

\textbf{Purpose}: * Illustrate concept of function design * Demonstrate
how functions can break down a process into simple components *
Demonstrate how component functions build on each other * Introduce idea
of functional groups * Motivate use of classes (to be introduced later)

\hypertarget{basic-insight}{%
\section{Basic Insight}\label{basic-insight}}

Functions contain any code, so they can contain functions. * Functions
can call other functions * Functions can define new functions

We create functions that call functions in order to break a complex
process into components. * Some functions focus on simple component
processes * Other functions combine these into higher order processes *
Some functions may be focused on computation, while others may be
focused on interacting with users or data sources * We can think of this
a division of labor, or ``separation of concerns,'' among functions

When you create groups of functions, they often form natural groups that
associated with a common process or task. * These function groups often
share variables in addition to calling each ohter

Let's look at some examples to illustrate these points.

\hypertarget{example-1-converting-temperatures}{%
\section{Example 1: Converting
Temperatures}\label{example-1-converting-temperatures}}

Here are three functions that work together to make a temperature
converter.

Notice how the last function integrates the first two.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ f\_to\_c(temp):  }
    \CommentTok{"""}
\CommentTok{    Converts F to C and returns a rounded result.}
\CommentTok{    Expects an integer and returns an integer.}
\CommentTok{    """}
    \ControlFlowTok{return} \BuiltInTok{round}\NormalTok{((temp }\OperatorTok{{-}} \DecValTok{32}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{ (}\DecValTok{5}\OperatorTok{/}\DecValTok{9}\NormalTok{))}
    
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ c\_to\_f(temp):  }
    \CommentTok{"""}
\CommentTok{    Converts C to F and returns a rounded result.}
\CommentTok{    Expects an integer and returns an integer.}
\CommentTok{    """}
    \ControlFlowTok{return} \BuiltInTok{round}\NormalTok{(temp }\OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{ (}\DecValTok{9}\OperatorTok{/}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{+} \DecValTok{32}\NormalTok{)}
    
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ convert(temp, scale): }
    \CommentTok{"""}
\CommentTok{    Combines conversion functions into a two{-}way converter.}
\CommentTok{    Expects a souce temp (int) and a target scale (\textquotesingle{}f\textquotesingle{} or \textquotesingle{}c\textquotesingle{}).}
\CommentTok{    """}
    \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ scale.lower() }\OperatorTok{==} \StringTok{"c"}\NormalTok{:}
        \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ f\_to\_c(temp)  }\CommentTok{\# function call to f\_to\_c}
    \ControlFlowTok{else}\NormalTok{:}
        \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ c\_to\_f(temp)  }\CommentTok{\# function call to c\_to\_f}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Now, here is function that combines the above functions into a
\textbf{user-facing interface} to the other functions.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\#| tags: []}
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ convert\_app():}
    \CommentTok{"""}
\CommentTok{    Provides a user{-}interface to the the conversion functions.}
\CommentTok{    """}
    
    \CommentTok{\# Get user input}
\NormalTok{    temp }\OperatorTok{=} \BuiltInTok{int}\NormalTok{(}\BuiltInTok{input}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Enter a temperature: "}\NormalTok{))                }
\NormalTok{    scale }\OperatorTok{=} \BuiltInTok{input}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Enter the scale to convert to: (c or f) "}\NormalTok{)[}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{].lower()}
    
    \CommentTok{\# Infer source scale, to be used in the output message}
    \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ scale }\OperatorTok{==} \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}c\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{:}
\NormalTok{        current\_scale }\OperatorTok{=} \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}f\textquotesingle{}}
    \ControlFlowTok{else}\NormalTok{:}
\NormalTok{        current\_scale }\OperatorTok{=} \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}c\textquotesingle{}}
    
    \CommentTok{\# Do the conversion}
\NormalTok{    converted }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ convert(temp, scale)}
    
    \CommentTok{\# Print results for user}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\SpecialStringTok{f"}\SpecialCharTok{\{}\NormalTok{temp}\SpecialCharTok{\}\{}\NormalTok{current\_scale}\SpecialCharTok{.}\NormalTok{upper()}\SpecialCharTok{\}}\SpecialStringTok{ is equal to }\SpecialCharTok{\{}\NormalTok{converted}\SpecialCharTok{\}\{}\NormalTok{scale}\SpecialCharTok{.}\NormalTok{upper()}\SpecialCharTok{\}}\SpecialStringTok{."}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{convert\_app()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{a-more-pythonic-solution}{%
\subsection{A More Pythonic Solution}\label{a-more-pythonic-solution}}

We replace if/then statements with dictionary logic.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\# Put your logic in the data structure}
\NormalTok{converters }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ \{}
    \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}c\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: }\KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ t: (t }\OperatorTok{{-}} \DecValTok{32}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{ (}\DecValTok{5}\OperatorTok{/}\DecValTok{9}\NormalTok{),}
    \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}f\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: }\KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ t: t }\OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{ (}\DecValTok{9}\OperatorTok{/}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{+} \DecValTok{32}
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ convert\_app2():}
    
    \CommentTok{\# Input from user}
\NormalTok{    source\_temp  }\OperatorTok{=} \BuiltInTok{int}\NormalTok{(}\BuiltInTok{input}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Enter a temperature: "}\NormalTok{))                }
\NormalTok{    target\_scale }\OperatorTok{=} \BuiltInTok{input}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Enter the scale to convert to: (c or f) "}\NormalTok{)}
    
    \CommentTok{\# Internal computations}
\NormalTok{    target\_temp  }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ converters[target\_scale](source\_temp)}
    \CommentTok{\# source\_scale = list(set(converters.keys()) {-} set(target\_scale))[0]}
\NormalTok{    source\_scale }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ (}\BuiltInTok{set}\NormalTok{(converters.keys()) }\OperatorTok{{-}} \BuiltInTok{set}\NormalTok{(target\_scale)).pop()}
    
    \CommentTok{\# Output to user}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(source\_temp, source\_scale, }\StringTok{"converted becomes:"}\NormalTok{ , }\BuiltInTok{round}\NormalTok{(target\_temp), target\_scale)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{convert\_app2()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{example-2-counting-vowels}{%
\section{Example 2: Counting Vowels}\label{example-2-counting-vowels}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\# Predicate functions {-} often used as helper functions that return True or False}

\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ is\_vowel(l):}
    \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ l }\OperatorTok{==} \StringTok{"a"} \KeywordTok{or}\NormalTok{ l }\OperatorTok{==} \StringTok{"e"} \KeywordTok{or}\NormalTok{ l }\OperatorTok{==} \StringTok{"i"} \KeywordTok{or}\NormalTok{ l }\OperatorTok{==} \StringTok{"o"} \KeywordTok{or}\NormalTok{ l }\OperatorTok{==} \StringTok{"u"}\NormalTok{:}
        \ControlFlowTok{return} \VariableTok{True}  \CommentTok{\# if the letter is a vowel, return True}
    \ControlFlowTok{else}\NormalTok{:}
        \ControlFlowTok{return} \VariableTok{False} \CommentTok{\# else, return False}
        
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ num\_vowels(my\_string):}
\NormalTok{    my\_string }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ my\_string.lower()}
\NormalTok{    count }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{0}
    \ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ i }\KeywordTok{in} \BuiltInTok{range}\NormalTok{(}\BuiltInTok{len}\NormalTok{(my\_string)): }\CommentTok{\# for each character}
        \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ is\_vowel(my\_string[i]):  }\CommentTok{\# call function above}
\NormalTok{            count }\OperatorTok{+=} \DecValTok{1}              \CommentTok{\# increment count if true}
    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ count}
    
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ vcounter():}
\NormalTok{    my\_str }\OperatorTok{=} \BuiltInTok{input}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Enter a string: "}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{    vcount }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ num\_vowels(my\_str)}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\SpecialStringTok{f"There are }\SpecialCharTok{\{}\NormalTok{vcount}\SpecialCharTok{\}}\SpecialStringTok{ vowels in the string."}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{vcounter()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{a-more-pythonic-solution-1}{%
\subsection{A More Pythonic Solution}\label{a-more-pythonic-solution-1}}

We can use a lambda function with a comprehension to replace the fisrt
two functions above.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{vowel\_count }\OperatorTok{=} \KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ x: }\BuiltInTok{len}\NormalTok{([char }\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ char }\KeywordTok{in}\NormalTok{ x.lower() }\ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ char }\KeywordTok{in} \StringTok{"aeiou"}\NormalTok{])}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{test\_str }\OperatorTok{=} \StringTok{"Whatever it is, it is what it is."}
\end{Highlighting}

\begin{Shaded}

\end{Highlighting}

\hypertarget{example-3-calculating-tax}{%
\section{Example 3: Calculating Tax}\label{example-3-calculating-tax}}

We write two related functions: * One to compute the \textbf{tax} based
on a \textbf{gross pay} and a \textbf{tax rate}. * One to compute the
\textbf{net pay} using the previous function.

In addition, we want to write some functions that use these functions to
interact with a user. * One to get the input value of the gross pay and
print the tax. * One to print the net pay based on the previous
function.

Note the division of labor, or ``separation of concerns'', in these
functions: * Some do calculative work * Some do interactive work

To compute tax, we have these data:

\begin{verbatim}
gross_pay    tax_rate
---------------------
0   - 240    0%
241 - 480    15%
481 - more   28% 
\end{verbatim}

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 0\tabcolsep) * \real{0.0694}}@{}}
\toprule()
\endhead
This time, we want to create a group of functions that expect some
global variables to exist and use these instead of return statements. \\
In the code below, we globalize any variables that are assigned in our
functions. \\
This allows them to be shared by all the other functions. \\
Note that this is effective when our global environment -- the
containing script -- contains only these functions. \\
Later in this course, we will look at mechanisms to segment our code in
this way. \\
\bottomrule()
\end{longtable}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ compute\_tax():}
    \CommentTok{"""}
\CommentTok{    Computes tax rate and applies to gross pay to get tax.}
\CommentTok{    Expects gross\_apy to be defined globally.}
\CommentTok{    Adds tax\_rate and tax to globals for use by other functins.}
\CommentTok{    """}

    \KeywordTok{global}\NormalTok{ tax\_rate, tax}

    \CommentTok{\# Get rate by lower bound}
    \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ gross\_pay }\OperatorTok{\textgreater{}} \DecValTok{480}\NormalTok{:}
\NormalTok{        tax\_rate }\OperatorTok{=} \FloatTok{.28}
    \ControlFlowTok{elif}\NormalTok{ gross\_pay }\OperatorTok{\textgreater{}} \DecValTok{240}\NormalTok{:}
\NormalTok{        tax\_rate }\OperatorTok{=} \FloatTok{.15}
    \ControlFlowTok{else}\NormalTok{:}
\NormalTok{        tax\_rate }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{0}
        
\NormalTok{    tax }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ gross\_pay }\OperatorTok{*}\NormalTok{ tax\_rate}
            
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ compute\_net\_pay():}
    \CommentTok{"""}
\CommentTok{    Computes net pay based on globals produced by compute\_tax().}
\CommentTok{    Expects gross\_pay and tax to be defined globally.}
\CommentTok{    Adds net\_pay to to globals.}
\CommentTok{    """}
    
    \KeywordTok{global}\NormalTok{ net\_pay}
    
\NormalTok{    net\_pay }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ gross\_pay }\OperatorTok{{-}}\NormalTok{ tax}

\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ get\_tax():   }
    \CommentTok{"""}
\CommentTok{    Computes and prints tax based on user input.}
\CommentTok{    Essentially a wrapper around compute\_tax().}
\CommentTok{    Adds gross\_pay to globals.}
\CommentTok{    """}
    
    \KeywordTok{global}\NormalTok{ gross\_pay}
    
\NormalTok{    gross\_pay }\OperatorTok{=} \BuiltInTok{int}\NormalTok{(}\BuiltInTok{input}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Enter your gross pay in dollars: "}\NormalTok{))                            }
    
\NormalTok{    compute\_tax()}
    
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\SpecialStringTok{f"Based on a tax rate of }\SpecialCharTok{\{}\BuiltInTok{round}\NormalTok{(tax\_rate }\OperatorTok{*} \DecValTok{100}\NormalTok{)}\SpecialCharTok{\}}\SpecialStringTok{\%, the tax you owe on $}\SpecialCharTok{\{}\NormalTok{gross\_pay}\SpecialCharTok{\}}\SpecialStringTok{ is $}\SpecialCharTok{\{}\BuiltInTok{round}\NormalTok{(tax)}\SpecialCharTok{\}}\SpecialStringTok{."}\NormalTok{)}
    
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ get\_net\_pay():}
    \CommentTok{"""}
\CommentTok{    Computes and prints net pay based on globals.}
\CommentTok{    """}
    
\NormalTok{    compute\_net\_pay()}
    
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\SpecialStringTok{f"Your take home (net) pay is $}\SpecialCharTok{\{}\BuiltInTok{round}\NormalTok{(net\_pay)}\SpecialCharTok{\}}\SpecialStringTok{."}\NormalTok{)}
    
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ do\_all():}
    \CommentTok{"Runs both user{-}facing functions."}
\NormalTok{    get\_tax()}
\NormalTok{    get\_net\_pay()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{get\_tax()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{get\_net\_pay()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{do\_all()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
