\hypertarget{boolean-filtering}{%
\section{Boolean Filtering}\label{boolean-filtering}}

It's very common to subset a dataframe based on some condition on the
data.

🔑 Note that even though we are filtering rows, we are not using
\texttt{.loc{[}{]}} or \texttt{.iloc{[}{]}} here.

Pandas knows what to do if you pass a boolean structure.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{iris.sepal\_length }\OperatorTok{\textgreater{}=} \FloatTok{7.5}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{iris[iris.sepal\_length }\OperatorTok{\textgreater{}=} \FloatTok{7.5}\NormalTok{]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{iris[(iris[}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}sepal\_length\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{ ]}\OperatorTok{\textgreater{}=} \FloatTok{4.5}\NormalTok{) }\OperatorTok{\&}\NormalTok{ (iris[}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}sepal\_length\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{] }\OperatorTok{\textless{}=} \FloatTok{4.7}\NormalTok{)]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{masking}{%
\subsection{Masking}\label{masking}}

Here's an example of \textbf{masking} using boolean conditions passed to
the dataframe selector:

Here are the \textbf{values} for the feature \texttt{sepal\ length}:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{iris.sepal\_length.values}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

And here are \textbf{the boolean values} generated by applying a
comparison operator to those values:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{mask }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ iris.sepal\_length }\OperatorTok{\textgreater{}=} \FloatTok{7.5}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{mask.values}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

The two sets of values have the same shape.

We can now overlay the logical values over the numeric ones and keep
only what is \texttt{True}:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{iris.sepal\_length[mask].values}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{working-with-missing-data}{%
\section{Working with Missing Data}\label{working-with-missing-data}}

Pandas primarily uses the data type \texttt{np.nan} from NumPy to
represent missing data.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{df\_miss }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.DataFrame(\{}
    \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}x\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{:[}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, np.nan, }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{], }
    \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}y\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{:[np.nan, np.nan, }\DecValTok{6}\NormalTok{]\}}
\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{df\_miss}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{dropna}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{.dropna()}}{.dropna()}}\label{dropna}}

This will drop all rows with missing data in any column.

\href{https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.dropna.html}{Details}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{df\_drop\_all }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ df\_miss.dropna()}
\NormalTok{df\_drop\_all}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

The \texttt{subset} parameter takes a list of column names to specify
which columns should have missing values.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{df\_drop\_x }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ df\_miss.dropna(subset}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{[}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}x\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{])}
\NormalTok{df\_drop\_x}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{fillna}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{.fillna()}}{.fillna()}}\label{fillna}}

This will replace missing values with whatever you set it to,
e.g.~\(0\)s.

\href{https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.fillna.html}{Details}

We can pass the results of an operation -- for example to peform simple
imputation, we can replace missing values in each column with the median
value of the respective column:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{df\_filled }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ df\_miss.fillna(df\_miss.median())}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{df\_filled}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Sort by values - \texttt{by} parameter takes string or list of strings -

This is \textbf{a highly useful} function for showing the frequency for

Parameters give the ability to sort by count or index, normalize, and

\href{https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/reference/api/pandas.Series.value_counts.html}{Details}

The methods returns a series that can be converted into a dataframe.

\begin{Shaded}

\NormalTok{SEPAL\_LENGTH }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ iris.sepal\_length.value\_counts().to\_frame(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}n\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{SEPAL\_LENGTH.sort\_index().plot.bar(figsize}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{8}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{), rot}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{45}\NormalTok{)}\OperatorTok{;}

\hypertarget{apply-lambda-functions-with-.apply}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{Apply Lambda Functions with
\texttt{.apply()}}{Apply Lambda Functions with .apply()}}\label{apply-lambda-functions-with-.apply}}

Apply a transformation to each record. Uses a \texttt{lambda} function.

The \texttt{apply()} method should be used after you have established
that you can't use a vectorized function.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{iris[}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}sepal\_len\_sq\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{] }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ iris.sepal\_length.}\BuiltInTok{apply}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ x: x}\OperatorTok{**}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{iris.head(}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Transformation involving multiple columns. Uses \texttt{axis=1} to
access columns.\\
Compute average of \texttt{sepal\_length}, \texttt{sepal\_width}:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{iris[}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}sepal\_len\_wid\_avg\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{] }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ iris[[}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}sepal\_length\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{,}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}sepal\_width\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{]].}\BuiltInTok{apply}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ x: (x.sepal\_length}\OperatorTok{+}\NormalTok{x.sepal\_width)}\OperatorTok{/}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, axis}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{iris.head()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Vectorized Version}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\OperatorTok{\%}\NormalTok{time iris.sepal\_length}\OperatorTok{**}\DecValTok{2}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Compare to \texttt{.apply()}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\OperatorTok{\%}\NormalTok{time iris.sepal\_length.}\BuiltInTok{apply}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{lambda}\NormalTok{ x: x}\OperatorTok{**}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{aggregation}{%
\section{Aggregation}\label{aggregation}}

Involves one or more of:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  splitting the data into groups
\item
  applying a function to each group
\item
  combining results
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{groupby}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{.groupby()}}{.groupby()}}\label{groupby}}

Compute mean of each column, grouped (separately) by species

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{iris.groupby(}\StringTok{"species"}\NormalTok{).mean()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{pd.pivot_table}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{pd.pivot\_table()}}{pd.pivot\_table()}}\label{pd.pivot_table}}

Apply a function \texttt{aggfunc} to selected values grouped by columns

\href{https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/reference/api/pandas.pivot_table.html}{Details}

Compute mean sepal length for each species:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{pd.pivot\_table(iris, values}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{"sepal\_length"}\NormalTok{, columns}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{[}\StringTok{"species"}\NormalTok{], aggfunc }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ np.mean)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{stacking-and-unstacking}{%
\section{Stacking and Unstacking}\label{stacking-and-unstacking}}

Similar to pivoting, but requires -- and takes advantage of -- indexes.

\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{iris\_w\_idx }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ iris.copy() }

\CommentTok{\#\# Give the original index a name}
\NormalTok{iris\_w\_idx.index.name }\OperatorTok{=} \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}obs\_id\textquotesingle{}}

\CommentTok{\#\# Create a multi{-}index, using \textasciigrave{}species\textasciigrave{} as part of the key.}
\NormalTok{iris\_w\_idx }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ iris\_w\_idx.reset\_index().set\_index([}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}species\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{,}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}obs\_id\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{])}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{iris\_w\_idx}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\NormalTok{iris\_wide }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ iris\_w\_idx.sepal\_length.unstack(fill\_value}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{).T}

\hypertarget{combining-dataframes}{%
\section{Combining DataFrames}\label{combining-dataframes}}

\hypertarget{pd.concat}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{pd.concat()}}{pd.concat()}}\label{pd.concat}}

Concatenate pandas objects along an axis.

\href{https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/reference/api/pandas.concat.html}{Details}

Create two dfs and vertically stack them

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{df1 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.DataFrame(np.random.randn(}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{))}
\NormalTok{df2 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.DataFrame(np.random.randn(}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{df1}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{df2}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Concat rows}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{df3 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.concat([df1, df2], axis}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{df3}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{Concat columns}

This assumes that the indexes represent IDs of specific things or
events.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{df4 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.concat([df1, df2], axis}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, keys}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{[}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}foo\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}bar\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{])}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{df4}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{df4.foo}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{merge}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{.merge()}}{.merge()}}\label{merge}}

SQL-style joining of tables (DataFrames) -- although Pandas has a
\texttt{.join()} method, too.

Important parameters include:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \texttt{how} : type of merge \{`left', `right', `outer', `inner',
  `cross'\}, default `inner'
\item
  \texttt{on} : names to join on
\end{itemize}

\href{https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.merge.html}{Details}

Create two tables, \texttt{left} and \texttt{right}. Then right join
them on \texttt{key}.\\
Right join means include all records from table on right.\\
The \texttt{key} is used for matching up the records.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\#| tags: []}
\NormalTok{left }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.DataFrame(\{}\StringTok{"key"}\NormalTok{: [}\StringTok{"jamie"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"bill"}\NormalTok{], }\StringTok{"lval"}\NormalTok{: [}\DecValTok{15}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{22}\NormalTok{]\})}
\NormalTok{right }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.DataFrame(\{}\StringTok{"key"}\NormalTok{: [}\StringTok{"jamie"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"bill"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"asher"}\NormalTok{], }\StringTok{"rval"}\NormalTok{: [}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{8}\NormalTok{]\})}

\NormalTok{joined }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.merge(left, right, on}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{"key"}\NormalTok{, how}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{"right"}\NormalTok{)}

\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}{-}{-}{-}left\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(left)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}}\CharTok{\textbackslash{}n}\StringTok{{-}{-}{-}right\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(right)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}}\CharTok{\textbackslash{}n}\StringTok{{-}{-}{-}joined\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(joined)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Notice the NaN inserted into the record with key=asher, since the left
table didn't contain the key.

\textbf{Matching column names}\\
In this next example, the value columns have the same name: \emph{val}.
Notice what happens to the column names.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\#| tags: []}
\NormalTok{left }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.DataFrame(\{}\StringTok{"key"}\NormalTok{: [}\StringTok{"jamie"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"bill"}\NormalTok{], }\StringTok{"val"}\NormalTok{: [}\DecValTok{15}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{22}\NormalTok{]\})}
\NormalTok{right }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.DataFrame(\{}\StringTok{"key"}\NormalTok{: [}\StringTok{"jamie"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"bill"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"asher"}\NormalTok{], }\StringTok{"val"}\NormalTok{: [}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{8}\NormalTok{]\})}

\NormalTok{joined }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.merge(left, right, on}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{"key"}\NormalTok{, how}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{"right"}\NormalTok{)}

\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}{-}{-}{-}left\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(left)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}}\CharTok{\textbackslash{}n}\StringTok{{-}{-}{-}right\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(right)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}}\CharTok{\textbackslash{}n}\StringTok{{-}{-}{-}joined\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(joined)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{join}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{.join()}}{.join()}}\label{join}}

An SQL-like joiner, but this one takes advantage of indexes.

Give our dataframes indexes and distinctive columns names.

\href{https://pandas.pydata.org/pandas-docs/stable/reference/api/pandas.DataFrame.join.html}{Details}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{left2 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ left.set\_index(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}key\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{).rename(columns}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{\{}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}val\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{:}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}val\_1\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{\})}
\NormalTok{right2 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ right.set\_index(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}key\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{).rename(columns}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{\{}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}val\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{:}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}val\_2\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{\})}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{left2}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{right2}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{right2.join(left2) }\CommentTok{\# Defaults to \textquotesingle{}inner\textquotesingle{}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{right2.join(left2, how}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}left\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{summary}{%
\subsection{Summary}\label{summary}}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Use \textbf{join} if you have shared indexes
\item
  Use \textbf{merge} if you do not have shared indexes
\item
  Use \textbf{concat} to combine based on shared indexes or columns
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{reshape-with-.reshape}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{Reshape with
\texttt{.reshape()}}{Reshape with .reshape()}}\label{reshape-with-.reshape}}

Changes the object's shape

We illustrate creating pandas Series, extracting array of length 6, and
reshaping to 3x2 array.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\# create a series }
\NormalTok{ser }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.Series([}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{8}\NormalTok{]) }

\CommentTok{\#\# extract values }
\NormalTok{vals }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ ser.values }

\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}orig data:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, vals)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}orig type:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\BuiltInTok{type}\NormalTok{(vals))}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}orig shape:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, vals.shape)}

\CommentTok{\#\# reshaping series}
\NormalTok{reshaped\_vals }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ vals.reshape((}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)) }

\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}}\CharTok{\textbackslash{}n}\StringTok{ reshaped vals:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(reshaped\_vals)}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}}\CharTok{\textbackslash{}n}\StringTok{ new type:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\BuiltInTok{type}\NormalTok{(reshaped\_vals))}
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}new shape:\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, reshaped\_vals.shape)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Including -1 as one of the dimensions tells numpy: infer this dimension
from the data and the other dimensions.

Example: enforce 3 columns:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{vals.reshape(}\OperatorTok{{-}}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Enforce 3 rows:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{vals.reshape(}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{,}\OperatorTok{{-}}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\textbf{IMPORTANT NOTE}

Notice the shape of original array: \texttt{(6,)}\\
This is a vector with one dimension, and is different from
two-dimensional \texttt{(6,1)} array

\hypertarget{categoricals}{%
\section{Categoricals}\label{categoricals}}

Categorical data takes discrete values where computation on the values
does not make sense.\\
Zip code is a typical example.

To include categoricals in models, they must be converted to numeric.

\hypertarget{nb-narrow-vs-wide-tables}{%
\chapter{NB: Narrow vs Wide Tables}\label{nb-narrow-vs-wide-tables}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\ImportTok{import}\NormalTok{ pandas }\ImportTok{as}\NormalTok{ pd}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\#| tags: []}
\NormalTok{pets }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.Series(}\StringTok{"cat dog ferret snake turtle parraot"}\NormalTok{.split()).sample(}\DecValTok{1000}\NormalTok{, replace}\OperatorTok{=}\VariableTok{True}\NormalTok{).to\_list()}
\NormalTok{people }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.Series(}\StringTok{"A B C D E F G"}\NormalTok{.split()).sample(}\DecValTok{1000}\NormalTok{, replace}\OperatorTok{=}\VariableTok{True}\NormalTok{).to\_list()   }
\NormalTok{NARROW }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.DataFrame(}\BuiltInTok{dict}\NormalTok{(pet}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{pets, owner}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{people)).groupby([}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}owner\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}pet\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{]).pet.count().to\_frame(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}n\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

This is a narrow table.

It has few columns and many rows.

Columns are types of things, and values in rows are either instances or
subtypes.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{NARROW}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{WIDE }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ NARROW.n.unstack()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

This is a wide table.

One column's values are projected onto the feature space (as columns).

The othe column becomes a unique list (as is the feature space).

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{WIDE}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Narrow columns are more manageable by databases.

Wide columns are more usable for analysis.

You can do these things with narrow tables using \texttt{.group\_by()}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{A }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ WIDE }\OperatorTok{/}\NormalTok{ WIDE.}\BuiltInTok{sum}\NormalTok{()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{B }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ WIDE.T }\OperatorTok{/}\NormalTok{ WIDE.T.}\BuiltInTok{sum}\NormalTok{()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\end{Highlighting}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{B.style.background\_gradient()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\NormalTok{NARROW.unstack()}

\hypertarget{what-is-oop}{%
\chapter{What is OOP?}\label{what-is-oop}}

\hypertarget{the-basic-idea}{%
\section{The Basic Idea}\label{the-basic-idea}}

The usual way that Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) is introduced to
students is as a natural way to describe things in the world.

The story told goes something like this:

\textbf{The world consists of a bunch of things.}

These things may be animate or inanimate, but they have two things in
common:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Attributes: qualities, traits, features
\item
  Behaviors: ways of interacting with other things
\end{itemize}

So, anything from an orange to the economy of France are things.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  The properties of an orange are its color, weight, species, etc.
\item
  The properties of the economy of France are its GDP, its industrial
  sectors, its rate of unemployment, etc.
\item
  The behaviors of an orange are things like being eaten, or rotting.
\item
  The behaviors of an economy are going into a recession, etc.
\end{itemize}

These things are called \textbf{objects}.

\textbf{All objects that exist are instances of abstract classes.}

Every object that exists is an instance of an abstract class.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  A specific orange is an instance of the class of Oranges.
\item
  France's economy is an instance of the class of National Economies.
\end{itemize}

\begin{tcolorbox}[enhanced jigsaw, colframe=quarto-callout-note-color-frame, title=\textcolor{quarto-callout-note-color}{\faInfo}\hspace{0.5em}{Note}, toprule=.15mm, opacitybacktitle=0.6, opacityback=0, arc=.35mm, colbacktitle=quarto-callout-note-color!10!white, bottomtitle=1mm, toptitle=1mm, titlerule=0mm, rightrule=.15mm, bottomrule=.15mm, coltitle=black, leftrule=.75mm, left=2mm, colback=white, breakable]

The nature of these classes raises an important philosophical question,
but we will not address this here.

\end{tcolorbox}

\textbf{Classes are organized into trees.}

Classes are organized into tree-like structures.

Specific classes inherit the attributes and behaviors of their parent
and ancestors, although they can override these as well.

So, an organge might have this lineage:

\texttt{Plant\ \textgreater{}\ Magnoliophyta\ \textgreater{}\ Magnoliopsida\ \textgreater{}\ Rosidae\ \textgreater{}\ Sapindales\ \textgreater{}\ Rutaceae\ \textgreater{}\ Citrus\ \textgreater{}\ Valencia\ Orange}

\begin{tcolorbox}[enhanced jigsaw, colframe=quarto-callout-note-color-frame, title=\textcolor{quarto-callout-note-color}{\faInfo}\hspace{0.5em}{Note}, toprule=.15mm, opacitybacktitle=0.6, opacityback=0, arc=.35mm, colbacktitle=quarto-callout-note-color!10!white, bottomtitle=1mm, toptitle=1mm, titlerule=0mm, rightrule=.15mm, bottomrule=.15mm, coltitle=black, leftrule=.75mm, left=2mm, colback=white, breakable]

The idea that the world is organized into a hierarchy of things
descending from some primary substance is ancient. Here is an example
from the European Middle Ages:

\end{tcolorbox}

\begin{figure}

{\centering \includegraphics{topics/../media/Porphyrian_Tree.png}

}

\caption{The Poryphyrian Tree}

\end{figure}

\hypertarget{relationship-to-coding}{%
\section{Relationship to Coding}\label{relationship-to-coding}}

OOP is based on the analogy that code can be organized in this way.

This is because software is often about the world -- we write software
to model things in the world.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  For example, if I wanted to write code simulate the traffic pattern of
  a city, I might start by creating a class called Car.
\item
  This Car would have properties, such as its make and model, but also
  behaviors like driving.
\item
  Then, in simulation program, I would create a bunch of Car instances
  and have them do things like drive on streets, etc.
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{another-way-to-look-at-it}{%
\section{Another Way to Look at It}\label{another-way-to-look-at-it}}

Now, although this way of looking at OOP is somewhat intuitive, it can
be misleading.

It is great for understanding the data structure that OOP uses.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  A tree-like organization of classes
\item
  Classes with attributes and behaviors
\end{itemize}

But the OO pattern is not always used to model things in the world.

Sometimes is just a good way to organize code -- OOP is a data structure
for the data that is code.

In other words, just as we say that dimension can refer to the world or
to the structure of data, so too can an object.

We use OOP to provide structure to our code, regardless of whether it
paints an accurate picture of the world.

\hypertarget{the-trinity}{%
\section{The Trinity}\label{the-trinity}}

OOP theory states that classes exhibit three fundamental properties that
make them powerful:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Encapsulation
\item
  Inheritance
\item
  Polymorphism
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Encapsulation} means that objects are self-contained. They have
their own scope, data, and logic. Ideally, they can be deployed in any
context and be shielded from external states.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Objects are meant to be black boxes to users: they should only be
  interacted with via the methods and attributes provided.
\item
  Nothing else should influence the state of the object except what it
  contains and what is passed to it.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Inheritance} means that classes can be subclasses of other
classes and thereby inherit their ancestor attributes and methods. -
Some programming languages allow only single inheritance -- classes can
have one parent. - Python supports multiple inheritance, but this can be
complicated to use.

\textbf{Polymorphism} means that methods can perform different behaviors
based on the arguments they are passed. - That is, a function can be
defined more than once in a class, as long as it each has a unique
\textbf{signature}. - A signature is the particular pattern of arguments
(parameters) a method has.

Today, we are only going to focus on \textbf{encapsulation} \ldots{}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Once upon a time, there was a movement to implement only this concept.
\item
  Microsoft, for example, developed a component-based approach to
  programming, where components are encapsulated unites of code without
  the complexity of inheritance.
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{nb-introducing-classes}{%
\chapter{NB: Introducing Classes}\label{nb-introducing-classes}}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  class
\item
  objects
\item
  instantiation
\item
  \texttt{\_\_init\_\_} function
\item
  attributes
\item
  methods
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{introduction-6}{%
\section{Introduction}\label{introduction-6}}

When we work with things and reason about them, we generally think about
their attributes, and what they can do.

For similar things, it can be helpful for group them into
\texttt{objects} such as cars, homes, databases, or logistic regression
models.

A \texttt{class} provides \textbf{a template} for creating an object,
and for working with the object. For the case of the logistic regression
model, it has \texttt{attributes} like:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  weights
\item
  an optional intercept term
\item
  the maximum number of iterations
\end{itemize}

These \textbf{attributes} help describe the object (they give the
object's \textbf{state}).

The logistic regression model has functionality such as: - the
optimization routine used in training - a prediction function

The behavior, or functionality, is supported by \textbf{methods}, which
are functions included in the class.

There are \textbf{tremendous benefits to programming with objects}, or
object-oriented programming (OOP), such as:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Objects are \textbf{natural} ways of defining, grouping,
  communicating, and thinking about things
\item
  Objects are convenient for \textbf{packaging together the data and
  functionality}. It concisely says: what is in this thing, and what
  does it do?
\item
  It is simple to create as \textbf{many copies} of the object as you'd
  like
\item
  For more complex objects, they can take on all the attributes and
  methods of the simpler object. this is called \texttt{inheritance}.
\end{itemize}

Ok, let's look at examples, starting with a very small, simple class.\\
The class contains: - a name (Ferrari458) - a docstring for a quick
description - an attribute, which is number of cylinders in the engine -
a method

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{class}\NormalTok{ Ferrari458:}
    \CommentTok{"""this is a Ferrari 458 object"""}
\NormalTok{    cylinders }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{8}

    \KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ print\_origin(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{):}
        \ControlFlowTok{return} \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}I was built in Italy!\textquotesingle{}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

You can learn about the class by printing the docstring:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{Ferrari458.\_\_doc\_\_}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

You can also get detailed help like this:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\BuiltInTok{help}\NormalTok{(Ferrari458)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Next, we create an object from the class (also called an
\texttt{instance} of the class).\\
It is called like a function with no parameters. The process is called
\texttt{instantiation.}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{myferrari }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ Ferrari458()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

We show the number of cylinders by using the \texttt{object.attribute}
format:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{myferrari.cylinders}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Then we call its method \texttt{print\_origin} to learn where this sweet
machine was built.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{myferrari.print\_origin()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

As a convention, methods take \texttt{self} as their first argument.
Methods can use \texttt{self.attribute} to extract their attributes.\\
Here is an example, with method \texttt{get\_cylinders}.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{class}\NormalTok{ Ferrari458\_v2:}
    \CommentTok{"""this is a Ferrari 458 object"""}
\NormalTok{    cylinders }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{8}

    \KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ print\_origin(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{):}
        \ControlFlowTok{return} \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}I was built in Italy!\textquotesingle{}}

    \KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ get\_cylinders(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{):}
        \ControlFlowTok{return} \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.cylinders}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{myferrari }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ Ferrari458\_v2()}
\NormalTok{myferrari.get\_cylinders()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{the-.__init__-method}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{The \texttt{.\_\_init\_\_()}
method}{The .\_\_init\_\_() method}}\label{the-.__init__-method}}

There is a special function called \texttt{\_\_init\_\_} that will
\textbf{initialize} objects for you when you create them.

Use it to supply more context-dependent information about your instance.

Let's look at another version of the class with \textbf{init}.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{class}\NormalTok{ Ferrari458\_v3:}
    \CommentTok{"""this is a Ferrari 458 object"""}
\NormalTok{    cylinders }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{8}
    
    \KeywordTok{def} \FunctionTok{\_\_init\_\_}\NormalTok{(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{, color):}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.color }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ color}

    \KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ print\_origin(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{):}
        \ControlFlowTok{return} \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}I was built in Italy!\textquotesingle{}}

    \KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ get\_color(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{):}
        \ControlFlowTok{return} \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.color}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

By adding the \texttt{\_\_init\_\_} function, we can create objects if
we pass the number of cylinders.

If we don't pass this parameter, there will be an error.

This is because we did not define a default value for the color argument
in our initialization method.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\#ferr1 = Ferrari458\_v3()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

This works:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{ferr1 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ Ferrari458\_v3(}\StringTok{"red"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

We can access the initialized attribute using the dot operator, just as
if it were declared at the top of the class:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{ferr1.color}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Or we can call the accessor method that we created.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{ferr1.get\_color()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Note that even though we initialized the car object with ``red'', we can
always change it:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{ferr1.color }\OperatorTok{=} \StringTok{"Cobalt"}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{ferr1.get\_color()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{the-meaning-of-self}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{The Meaning of
\texttt{self}}{The Meaning of self}}\label{the-meaning-of-self}}

Note the presence of an argument and variable called
\textbf{\texttt{self} in the method definitions}. - This stands for the
intantiated object itself.

So, when you create an object like so:

\begin{itemize}
\item
\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{foo }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ Foo()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\item
  \texttt{foo} is represented in the class definition as \texttt{self}.
\end{itemize}

If you want your method to access the other attributes and methods in an
object, \textbf{you need to put self as its first argument}. - Note that
when you use the method with an instance, you don't pass the object name
as an argument - The object name is passed implicitly by Python, since
it knows which object called the methid

You can use any valid name you want for the name of the object itself,
but the convention is to use \texttt{self}.

Note that \texttt{self} is \textbf{only used within the methods} of a
class, not outside of it. - Like functions, they don't know what's
outside of them, nor does the containing code know what's inside of
them. - The \texttt{self} variable is the mechanism that allows methods
to share data without having to pass and return a bunch of variables.

Think of \texttt{self} as a \textbf{data structure that stores the
program itself} - In this sense, it's similar to \textbf{recursion}: A
class definition contains a reference to itself! - But remember, the
class definition is not a thing -- it's a template. - \texttt{self} is
just a pronoun that allows an instance to access it's own state.

\hypertarget{summary-1}{%
\section{Summary}\label{summary-1}}

An \textbf{cobject} is a self-contained bundle of \textbf{methods and
attributes}. * Methods are basically functions. * Attributes are
basically variables.

A \textbf{class} definition is a \textbf{template} for creating objects.
* Objects are \textbf{class instances}. * Classes are \textbf{onbject
types}.

Objects have \textbf{their own scope}, like functions. * They are meant
to \textbf{exchange information} with their environment only through
accessing attributes and calling methods

When objects are first created, \textbf{they often expect to have data
passed to them}. * This is called \textbf{initializing} the object. *
These data are handled internally by the \texttt{.\_\_init\_\_()}
method. * Data that are passed this way can be \textbf{overridden} by
accessing the attributes they assigned to.

The methods of a class begin with \texttt{self} as the first argument. *
This stands for \textbf{the instance itself}. * \textbf{All methods and
attributes are avaible} to all other methods in the object
\textbf{through the \texttt{self} object}.

If a method does not have \texttt{self} as its first argument, it cannot
access the internal state or methods of the object. * The internal state
is just the attributes and their current values. * These are called
\textbf{static} methods. * Static methods are useful in providing
functions to the environment in which their containing object is
instantiated.

\textbf{There is a lot more to the subject, but this is good enough to
get started!}

\hypertarget{nb-classes-example}{%
\chapter{NB: Classes Example}\label{nb-classes-example}}

\hypertarget{set-up-1}{%
\section{Set Up}\label{set-up-1}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\ImportTok{import}\NormalTok{ pandas }\ImportTok{as}\NormalTok{ pd}
\ImportTok{import}\NormalTok{ numpy }\ImportTok{as}\NormalTok{ np}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{method-1-nothing-special}{%
\section{Method 1: Nothing Special}\label{method-1-nothing-special}}

We define a set of functions that work in a sequence, where the return
value of one is the argument of the other.

\hypertarget{define-functions}{%
\subsection{Define Functions}\label{define-functions}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ create\_die(weights):}
\NormalTok{    n\_sides }\OperatorTok{=} \BuiltInTok{len}\NormalTok{(weights)}
\NormalTok{    my\_probs }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ [i}\OperatorTok{/}\BuiltInTok{sum}\NormalTok{(weights) }\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ i }\KeywordTok{in}\NormalTok{ weights]}
\NormalTok{    my\_die }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.DataFrame(\{}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}side\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: }\BuiltInTok{range}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, n\_sides }\OperatorTok{+} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{),}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}weights\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: my\_probs}
\NormalTok{    \})}
    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ my\_die}

\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ roll\_dice(my\_die, n\_rolls}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{):}
\NormalTok{    results }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ []}
    \ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ i }\KeywordTok{in} \BuiltInTok{range}\NormalTok{(n\_rolls):}
\NormalTok{        result }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ my\_die.side.sample(weights}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{my\_die.weights).values[}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{        results.append(result)}
    \ControlFlowTok{return}\NormalTok{ pd.Series(results)}

\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ plot\_results(my\_results):}
\NormalTok{    my\_results.value\_counts().sort\_index().plot.bar()}\OperatorTok{;}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{create-instances}{%
\subsection{Create Instances}\label{create-instances}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{n\_rolls }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{10}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{fair\_die }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ create\_die([}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{])}
\NormalTok{fair\_results }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ roll\_dice(fair\_die, n\_rolls)}
\NormalTok{plot\_results(fair\_results)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{unfair\_die }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ create\_die([}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{])}
\NormalTok{unfair\_results }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ roll\_dice(unfair\_die, n\_rolls)}
\NormalTok{plot\_results(unfair\_results)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{doing-it-all-at-once}{%
\subsection{Doing it all at once}\label{doing-it-all-at-once}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ do\_it\_all(weights):}
\NormalTok{    plot\_results(roll\_dice(create\_die(weights), n\_rolls))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{do\_it\_all(roll\_dice(create\_die([}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{]), n\_rolls))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{method-2-with-globals}{%
\section{Method 2: With Globals}\label{method-2-with-globals}}

\hypertarget{define-a-shared-data-structure}{%
\subsection{Define a Shared Data
Structure}\label{define-a-shared-data-structure}}

We create a dictionary called \texttt{config} to store our instance
data.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{config }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ \{\} }\CommentTok{\# We expect this to have the same keys}
\NormalTok{n\_rolls2 }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{10}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{define-methods}{%
\subsection{Define Methods}\label{define-methods}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ create\_die2(die\_id):}
    \KeywordTok{global}\NormalTok{ config}
\NormalTok{    config[die\_id][}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}die\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{] }\OperatorTok{=} \VariableTok{None}
\NormalTok{    weights }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ config[die\_id][}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}weights\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{    n\_sides }\OperatorTok{=} \BuiltInTok{len}\NormalTok{(weights)}
\NormalTok{    my\_probs }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ [i}\OperatorTok{/}\BuiltInTok{sum}\NormalTok{(weights) }\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ i }\KeywordTok{in}\NormalTok{ weights]}
\NormalTok{    config[die\_id][}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}die\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{] }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.DataFrame(\{}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}side\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: }\BuiltInTok{range}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, n\_sides }\OperatorTok{+} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{),}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}weights\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: my\_probs}
\NormalTok{    \})}

\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ roll\_dice2(die\_id):}
    \KeywordTok{global}\NormalTok{ config}
    \KeywordTok{global}\NormalTok{ n\_rolls2}
\NormalTok{    config[die\_id][}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}results\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{] }\OperatorTok{=} \VariableTok{None}
\NormalTok{    my\_die }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ config[die\_id][}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}die\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{    results }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ []}
    \ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ i }\KeywordTok{in} \BuiltInTok{range}\NormalTok{(n\_rolls2):}
\NormalTok{        result }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ my\_die.side.sample(weights}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{my\_die.weights).values[}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{        results.append(result)}
\NormalTok{    config[die\_id][}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}results\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{] }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.Series(results)}

\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ plot\_results2(die\_id):}
    \KeywordTok{global}\NormalTok{ config}
\NormalTok{    my\_results }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ config[die\_id][}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}results\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{    my\_results.value\_counts().sort\_index().plot.bar()}\OperatorTok{;}

\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ do\_it\_all2(die\_id):}
    \KeywordTok{global}\NormalTok{ config}
    \KeywordTok{global}\NormalTok{ n\_rolls2}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Die ID:"}\NormalTok{, die\_id)}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Weights:"}\NormalTok{, config[die\_id][}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}weights\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{])}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Rolls:"}\NormalTok{, n\_rolls2)}
\NormalTok{    create\_die2(die\_id)}
\NormalTok{    roll\_dice2(die\_id)}
\NormalTok{    plot\_results2(die\_id)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{populate-config}{%
\subsection{Populate Config}\label{populate-config}}

We populate our configuration config with some instances.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{config }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ \{}
    \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}fair\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: \{}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}weights\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: [}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{    \},}
    \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}unfair\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: \{}
        \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}weights\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: [}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{100}\NormalTok{],}
\NormalTok{    \}}
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{call-main-function}{%
\subsection{Call Main Function}\label{call-main-function}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{do\_it\_all2(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}fair\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{do\_it\_all2(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}unfair\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{n\_rolls2 }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{1000} \CommentTok{\# We change this, but it will affect all uses of the functions until we change it.}
\NormalTok{do\_it\_all2(}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}unfair\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{method-3-as-class}{%
\section{Method 3: As Class}\label{method-3-as-class}}

Define a class that contains the config data structure and all the
functions as attributes and methods.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{class}\NormalTok{ DieGame():}
    
\NormalTok{    n\_rolls }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{10}
\NormalTok{    weights }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ [}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{]}
    
    \KeywordTok{def} \FunctionTok{\_\_init\_\_}\NormalTok{(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{):}
        \ControlFlowTok{return} \VariableTok{None}
        
    \KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ create\_die(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{):}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.n\_sides }\OperatorTok{=} \BuiltInTok{len}\NormalTok{(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.weights)}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.my\_probs }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ [i}\OperatorTok{/}\BuiltInTok{sum}\NormalTok{(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.weights) }\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ i }\KeywordTok{in} \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.weights]}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.die }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.DataFrame(\{}
            \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}side\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: }\BuiltInTok{range}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.n\_sides }\OperatorTok{+} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{),}
            \StringTok{\textquotesingle{}weights\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{: }\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.my\_probs}
\NormalTok{        \})}
    
    \KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ roll\_die(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{):}
\NormalTok{        results }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ []}
        \ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ i }\KeywordTok{in} \BuiltInTok{range}\NormalTok{(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.n\_rolls):}
\NormalTok{            result }\OperatorTok{=} \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.die.side.sample(weights}\OperatorTok{=}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.die.weights).values[}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{            results.append(result)}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.results }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.Series(results)        }
        
    \KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ plot\_results(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{):}
\NormalTok{        prob\_model }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.Series(\{i}\OperatorTok{+}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{:}\BuiltInTok{round}\NormalTok{(p, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{) }\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ i, p }\KeywordTok{in} \BuiltInTok{enumerate}\NormalTok{(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.my\_probs)\})}
        \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Sides:"}\NormalTok{, }\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.n\_sides)}
        \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Model:"}\NormalTok{)}
        \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(prob\_model)}
        \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Rolls:"}\NormalTok{, }\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.n\_rolls)}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.results.value\_counts().sort\_index().plot.bar(rot}\OperatorTok{=}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{)}\OperatorTok{;}
        
    \CommentTok{\# We add another method because it\textquotesingle{}s so easy :{-})}
    \KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ plot\_probs(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{):}
\NormalTok{        pd.Series(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.my\_probs).plot.pie(title}\OperatorTok{=}\StringTok{"Die Model"}\NormalTok{)}
        
    \KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ do\_it\_all(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{):}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.create\_die()}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.roll\_die()}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.plot\_results()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{game\_1 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ DieGame()}
\NormalTok{game\_1.n\_rolls }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{100}
\NormalTok{game\_1.do\_it\_all()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{game\_1.plot\_probs()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{game\_2 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ DieGame()}
\NormalTok{game\_2.n\_rolls }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{100}
\NormalTok{game\_2.weights }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ [}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{game\_2.do\_it\_all()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{game\_2.plot\_probs()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{conclusions}{%
\section{Conclusions}\label{conclusions}}

The OOP approach handles scoping issues as well as data management.

Notice how the dictionary is replaced by the object.

Not only does it provide a place to store the data, it also provides a
schema for it: * You don't need to remember what keys to put in the
\texttt{data} dictionary of method 2. The object specifies them.

Notice also that we don't pass arguments to the object as we do with
functions (although we can).

We assign values to attributes directly.

\textbf{Can you think of any other advantages or disadvantages?}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\# Import class dependencies here}
\ImportTok{import}\NormalTok{ pandas }\ImportTok{as}\NormalTok{ pd}

\CommentTok{    Extensive docstring describing structure and function of class.}
\CommentTok{    """}

\hypertarget{nb-understanding-static-attributes}{%
\chapter{NB: Understanding Static
Attributes}\label{nb-understanding-static-attributes}}

\textbf{Purpose}: To demonstrate how class and instance attributes are
related to each other.

\hypertarget{a-simple-example}{%
\section{A Simple Example}\label{a-simple-example}}

We define a class with one attribute.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{class}\NormalTok{ Foo(): x }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{1}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

We create an instance of the class.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{foo1 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ Foo()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

We demonstrate that the class defines the value for the instance.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{foo1.x, Foo.x}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

We demonstrate that the instance changes if the class does.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{Foo.x }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{2}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{foo1.x, Foo.x}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Now we override the class attribute with the local.

This is similar to how we can override a global with a local.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{foo1.x }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{3}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{foo1.x, Foo.x}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

We demonstrate that the instance attribute is now unaffected by the
global.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{Foo.x }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{4}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{foo1.x, Foo.x}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{a-cool-trick}{%
\section{A Cool Trick}\label{a-cool-trick}}

You can define an empty class and add attributes as you go.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{class}\NormalTok{ Bar:}
    \ControlFlowTok{pass}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{bar1 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ Bar()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{bar1.x }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{1}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{bar1.x}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Since we defined an instance attribute, the class remains unchanged.

So, this will throw an error:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{Bar.x}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

We define another instance, but this time we add an attribute to the
class.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{bar2 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ Bar()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{Bar.x }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{2}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Notice how the instance has the new attribute, even though it was added
to the class after the instance was created.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{bar2.x, Bar.x}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{mutable-statics}{%
\section{Mutable Statics}\label{mutable-statics}}

There is an interesting gotcha regarding static attributes in Python.

Lists and other mutable data structures can be static and yet have their
values modified by instances.

This is kind of weird.

To demonstrate, we define a class with two instance variables, one a
scalar and one a list.

We define a method to alter the value of each.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\#| tags: []}
\KeywordTok{class}\NormalTok{ WithStatic():}
    
\NormalTok{    foo }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{0}  \CommentTok{\# The value is NOT affected by instances}
\NormalTok{    bar }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ [] }\CommentTok{\# The values ARE afftected by instances}
    
    \KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ add\_one(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{):}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.foo }\OperatorTok{+=} \DecValTok{1}       \CommentTok{\# This does NOT affect the static attribute}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.bar.append(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)  }\CommentTok{\# This DOES affect the static attribute, only its values}
        
    \KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ replace\_bar(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{, new\_list }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ []):}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.bar }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ new\_list }\CommentTok{\# This replaces the list itself}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

We define a function to compare an instance and its class to see how
static attributes are affected by instances.

Notice the \texttt{getattr()} method -- this allows you to get the value
of an attribute using a literal value for the attribute name.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ my\_test (my\_class, my\_instance, my\_vars}\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{[]):}
    \ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ my\_var }\KeywordTok{in}\NormalTok{ my\_vars:}
\NormalTok{        i }\OperatorTok{=} \BuiltInTok{getattr}\NormalTok{(my\_instance, my\_var)}
\NormalTok{        c }\OperatorTok{=} \BuiltInTok{getattr}\NormalTok{(my\_class, my\_var)}
        \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\SpecialStringTok{f\textquotesingle{}i.}\SpecialCharTok{\{}\NormalTok{my\_var}\SpecialCharTok{\}}\SpecialStringTok{ =\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, i)}
        \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\SpecialStringTok{f\textquotesingle{}c.}\SpecialCharTok{\{}\NormalTok{my\_var}\SpecialCharTok{\}}\SpecialStringTok{ =\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, c)}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

We define an instance and compare the values.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{with\_static1 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ WithStatic()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{my\_test(WithStatic, with\_static1, [}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}foo\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}bar\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{])}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Now we increment the attributes and see the results.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{with\_static1.add\_one()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

The method does disconnect the instance \texttt{foo} from the class
\texttt{foo}.

But it does not disconnect the instance \texttt{bar} from the class
\texttt{bar}.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{my\_test(WithStatic, with\_static1, [}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}foo\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}bar\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{])}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

We do it again to drive the point home.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{with\_static1.add\_one()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{my\_test(WithStatic, with\_static1, [}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}foo\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}bar\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{])}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Now, let's replace list itself in the instance.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{with\_static1.replace\_bar()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ i }\KeywordTok{in} \BuiltInTok{range}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{):}
\NormalTok{    with\_static1.add\_one()}
\NormalTok{    my\_test(WithStatic, with\_static1, [}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}foo\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}bar\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{])}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

We define a second instance.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{with\_static2 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ WithStatic()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

The new instance has the original value of \texttt{foo}.

However, it starts of with the modified value of \texttt{bar} before it
was replaced.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{my\_test(WithStatic, with\_static2, [}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}foo\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}bar\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{])}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

We do it a few more times to drive the point home.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ i }\KeywordTok{in} \BuiltInTok{range}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{):}
\NormalTok{    with\_static2.add\_one()}
\NormalTok{    my\_test(WithStatic, with\_static2, [}\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}foo\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{\textquotesingle{}bar\textquotesingle{}}\NormalTok{])}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{testing-and-verification}{%
\chapter{Testing and Verification}\label{testing-and-verification}}

Definitions

Before we get started, let's review some definitions.

verification

Shows that the code meets the requirement specification~Example: You
verify that I wrote the program you asked me to write.

validation

Shows that the code meets the real requirements Example: You show that
the program is a valid solution to the user's problem.

quality

Suggests that validations falls on a scale, not a black-and-white idea.
Defining the scale can be difficult.

specification

A precise and detailed statement about the properties some things must
have

Design specification: exact instructions for how to build something

Requirements specifications: exact statements about what should be built

Specifications are very important. Not only are they used to guide the
creation of the project, but also they're{~}vital for program testing
and verification. That is, if you don't have specifications for the
product, you cannot verify that you're doing the right thing. Likewise,
if behavior is not defined, then it becomes difficult to know what
is{~}incorrect{~}behavior.

Edsger Dijkstra{~}was a famous computer scientist and A. M. Turing award
winner. This quotation by him is a great one and very true. Even if you
write a test suite of carefully crafted test cases, and if they all run
and pass, it doesn't mean that no further bugs exist.

It is much easier to prove the existence of something than to disprove
the existence of something.{~}This realization should motivate us to
learn how to create carefully crafted unit tests so that we can test as
much as we can.

``Program testing can effectively show the presence of bugs but is
hopeless for showing their absence.''--Edsger Dijkstra

Formal Verification

Formal verification involves proof. There are three types:

Hand-written, hand-checked

Hand-written, machine-checked (proof-carrying code)

Machine-written, machine-checked (static analysis)

None of them are very widely used yet, but the latter two are increasing
in popularity. Formal verification is complex, difficult, and takes a
great deal of effort.

Empirical Testing

Instead of formal verification, correctness is demonstrated through
empirical testing. Empirical testing shows it works on several inputs.
In general, testing is:

A lot easier than proof

A lot harder (and more involved) than writing code~

Types of Empirical Testing

There are many kinds of testing, but we will focus on unit testing in
this module. Two other kinds of testing are integration and acceptance
(beta) testing, which are out of the scope of this lesson. See below for
a short description.

Unit Testing

Write code that tests the smallest possible units of the spec (must
attempt to test every flow path). The programmer does unit testing as
part of the coding process.

Integration Testing

Test that units work together.

Acceptance Testing (Beta Testing)

Give product to real users to try it out.

Flow Path

A flow path is a unique execution sequence through a program unit. It is
done as part of the coding process by the programmer. A good set of test
data makes sure every possible path is followed (tests every possible
behavior). Because loops are able to execute an arbitrarily large number
of times, and because there ~potentially are an infinite number of
inputs into a program, there are virtually an infinite number of flow
paths. Exhaustive testing is usually impossible. However, we can
overcome these odds by being clever about the kinds of tests that we
write. We'll also learn about equivalence classes, which also help us
overcome this hurdle.

Example of code showing various flow paths. For example, starting at
Stmt1, then the condition of the while loop (C1) is true, so that takes
us to the condition of the if statement (C2) but maybe this is false, so
we end up in the else portion, Stmt3. This is an example of a flow path
starting at Stmt1 and ending up at Stmt3. In other words, there are many
paths through a given program.

\hypertarget{overview-2}{%
\section{Overview}\label{overview-2}}

\begin{quote}
All happy families are alike, but every unhappy family is unhappy in its
own way.\\
-- Leo Tolstoy, \emph{Anna Karenina}, 1878.
\end{quote}

There are two ways that programs can succeed of fail:

They can meet or not meet the motiving \textbf{requirements} for the
code. - Does it do what is is supposed to do? - Does it add value to a
process? - Is it ethical? Does it do harm?

They can \textbf{work or not work}: - Does the run at all? - Is the code
brittle or buggy? - Is it sensitive to contextual factors like bad user
input or a bad database connection? - Does the code work but produce
incorrect outcomes?

These lead to \textbf{two practices}: * Strategic: \textbf{Project
management} * Tactical: \textbf{Testing and debugging}

Today, we will focus on some concepts and tools for the latter. * We
want to know whether our code is \textbf{working or not}. * We want to
know if our code is of a \textbf{high quality}.

\textbf{Approaches to quality} * Through good \textbf{design} * Throigh
principled \textbf{testing}

\textbf{Some design principles} * Favor the \textbf{simple over the
complex} * Don't confuse the easy with the simple! * Invest in
\textbf{data design} to simplify algorithm design * Write
\textbf{literate code} * Given a choice, use tools that are
\textbf{documented} and have a \textbf{user community} * Many other
things :-)

\textbf{Some testing activities} * Syntax checking * Debugging * Ad hoc
testing * Unit-testing * User testing

\textbf{Some concepts} * Beware of \textbf{silent failures} * Testing
for \textbf{the absence of bugs} is impossible - Like Popper's concept
of falsifiability

\hypertarget{tools-and-concepts-for-testing}{%
\section{Tools and Concepts for
Testing}\label{tools-and-concepts-for-testing}}

Programming languages offer many tools for testing.

These include mechanisms to define and capture errors in code.

We call these errors \textbf{exceptions}. - An exception is an event
that occurs during the execution of a program that disrupts the normal
flow of the program's instructions.

We call we call dealing with these errors \textbf{exception handling}. -
When a Python script encounters a code failure, it raises an exception.

\hypertarget{pythons-tools}{%
\section{Python's Tools}\label{pythons-tools}}

\textbf{Exceptions} - A Python \textbf{object} that represents an error
- Objects that classify kinds of errors - Coders can define these

\textbf{Exception Handlers} - Control structures and functions to deal
with exceptions - \texttt{try}/\texttt{except} - \texttt{raise} -
\texttt{assert}

\textbf{Unit Testing Frameworks} - Robot - PyTest - \textbf{Unittest} -
DocTest - Nose2 - Testify

\hypertarget{errors-and-exceptions}{%
\section{Errors and Exceptions}\label{errors-and-exceptions}}

A common technical interview question: Explain the difference between an
\textbf{error} and an \textbf{exception}.

An \textbf{error} is a serious problem that a reasonable application
should not try to catch.\\
An error will stop execution. It means the code if broken and needs to
be rewritten.

An \textbf{exception} is an issue that is expected or known to occur
(e.g., division by zero).\\
Software must handle exceptions. For example, one bad row of data
shouldn't bring down the application.

\hypertarget{some-common-built-in-exceptions}{%
\section{Some Common Built-in
Exceptions}\label{some-common-built-in-exceptions}}

Python comes with a number of predefined exceptions.

Libraries introduce new ones, too.

They used in \texttt{raise} statement by the authors of programs when a
possible error is anticipated.

Here are some common examples.

\hypertarget{zerodivisionerror}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{ZeroDivisionError}}{ZeroDivisionError}}\label{zerodivisionerror}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\DecValTok{3} \OperatorTok{/} \DecValTok{0}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{syntax-error}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{Syntax\ Error}}{Syntax Error}}\label{syntax-error}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\# if{-}statement missing colon at end}

\ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ x }\OperatorTok{\textgreater{}} \DecValTok{0}
  \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"uh oh"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{nameerror}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{NameError}}{NameError}}\label{nameerror}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\# references an undefined variable}

\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(x)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{indexerror}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{IndexError}}{IndexError}}\label{indexerror}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\# loop goes off the end of the list}

\NormalTok{lst }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ [}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{]}

\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ i }\KeywordTok{in} \BuiltInTok{range}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{):}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(lst[i])}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{exception-handling-with-tryexcept}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{Exception Handling with
\texttt{try/except}}{Exception Handling with try/except}}\label{exception-handling-with-tryexcept}}

We use \texttt{try/except} blocks to handle exceptions in our code.

These blocks work as follows: * The \texttt{try} block will contain a
statement. * If the statement fails, the the flow goes to the
\texttt{except} block. * The exception block will have code to handle
the error, rather than halting the program.

The process is very similar to \texttt{if/then}: * \textbf{If} there is
an \textbf{error}, \textbf{then} raise an \textbf{excpetion}.

Multiple \texttt{except} statements may be given, to handle specific
exceptions.

Below, we give a catch-all \texttt{except} for any kind of exception.

An \textbf{excpetion} is a mistake that will halt the execution of code.
* For example, trying to access a dictionary key that does not exit. *
Or, a database connection fails. * Very often, execeptions are caused by
an external dependency failing, such as another system or the user.

Let's try referencing a variable that doesn't exist with no exception
handling.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(a)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Now let's try referencing a variable that doesn't exist with a
\texttt{try/except} block to handle the exception.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\ControlFlowTok{try}\NormalTok{:}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(a)}
\ControlFlowTok{except}\NormalTok{:}
   \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"caught an exception"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{assert-statements}{%
\section{Assert Statements}\label{assert-statements}}

Another to catch errors before they happen is to test if computations
turned out as expected.

We use \texttt{assert} to verify an expression is True.\\
- if expression is True, nothing happens. - if expression is False,
Python raises an \texttt{AssertionError} exception.

Assert statements have the followinf syntax:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\ControlFlowTok{assert}\NormalTok{ Expression[, Arguments]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

where \texttt{{[},\ Arguments{]}} denotes optional arguments.

For example, let's say a program is expecting three arguments to be
passed from the command line.

The variable \texttt{num\_args} counts the arguments.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{num\_args }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{3}

\ControlFlowTok{assert}\NormalTok{ num\_args }\OperatorTok{==} \DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"number of arguments must be 3!"}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

The \texttt{assert} evaluates to True, and things proceed normally
without exception.

If we change \texttt{num\_args\ =\ 4} this will throw an
\texttt{AssertionError} with the provided message.

The program then stops.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{num\_args }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{4}

\ControlFlowTok{assert}\NormalTok{ num\_args }\OperatorTok{==} \DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"number of arguments must be 3!"}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

If the \texttt{assert} is not given a message, it throws
\texttt{AssertionError:}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{num\_args }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{4}

\ControlFlowTok{assert}\NormalTok{ num\_args }\OperatorTok{==} \DecValTok{3}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\ControlFlowTok{try}\NormalTok{:}
    \ControlFlowTok{assert}\NormalTok{ num\_args }\OperatorTok{==} \DecValTok{3}
\ControlFlowTok{except}\NormalTok{:}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Got an error"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\ControlFlowTok{try}\NormalTok{:}
    \ControlFlowTok{assert}\NormalTok{ num\_args }\OperatorTok{==} \DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"Number of arguments must be 3!"}
\ControlFlowTok{except} \PreprocessorTok{AssertionError} \ImportTok{as}\NormalTok{ e:}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(e)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{raise}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{raise()}}{raise()}}\label{raise}}

Exceptions can be \textbf{raised}, too.

Use this if you want to halt the program and let other code that is
using this code handle it.\textbar{}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\ControlFlowTok{try}\NormalTok{:}
    \DecValTok{10}\OperatorTok{/}\DecValTok{0}
\ControlFlowTok{except}\NormalTok{:}
    \ControlFlowTok{raise} \PreprocessorTok{ZeroDivisionError}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Hey, you can\textquotesingle{}t divide by zero!"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\ControlFlowTok{raise} \PreprocessorTok{IndexError}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Bad Index"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{nb-unit-testing-with-unittest}{%
\chapter{NB: Unit Testing with
Unittest}\label{nb-unit-testing-with-unittest}}

\hypertarget{unit-testing}{%
\section{Unit Testing}\label{unit-testing}}

Unit testing is a testing technique in which \textbf{individual modules
are tested} to determine if there are any issues by the developer
himself.

It is concerned with \textbf{functional correctness} of the stand-alone
modules.

The main aim is to \textbf{isolate each unit} of the system to identify,
analyze and fix the defects.

These units are typicallly functions and methods.

\hypertarget{benefits-of-unit-testing}{%
\section{Benefits of Unit Testing}\label{benefits-of-unit-testing}}

Developers can work in a \textbf{predictable} way on developing code.

Developers can \textbf{write their own unit tests}.

You can get \textbf{a rapid response} for testing small changes

Also:

Reduces \textbf{defects in the newly developed features} or reduces bugs
when changing the existing functionality.

Reduces \textbf{cost of testing}, since defects are captured in very
early phase.

\textbf{Improves design} and allows better refactoring of code.

Testing in Python is a huge topic and can come with a lot of complexity,
but it doesn't need to be hard. You can get started creating simple
tests for your application in a few easy steps and then build on it from
there.

\hypertarget{the-unittest-framework}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{The \texttt{unittest}
Framework}{The unittest Framework}}\label{the-unittest-framework}}

One of the popular unit testing frameworks is Unittest. It is works well
and is easy to use.

There are other tools, though -- here's
\href{https://www.softwaretestinghelp.com/python-testing-frameworks/}{a
comparison of 6 Python testing frameworks}.

\hypertarget{the-basic-idea-1}{%
\section{The Basic Idea}\label{the-basic-idea-1}}

The Unittest framework provides you with \textbf{a bunch of
\texttt{assert} methods}, which are essentially wrappers around Python's
built-in \texttt{assert} function.

The basic idea is to \textbf{write functions that test other functions}
by using these assert methods \textbf{instead of peppering your code}
with them.

Unittest provides \textbf{many assert methods} -- see this
\href{https://kapeli.com/cheat_sheets/Python_unittest_Assertions.docset/Contents/Resources/Documents/index}{cheat
sheet} for more.

We will focus on three: * \texttt{assertTrue()} * \texttt{assertFalse()}
* \texttt{assertEqual()}

\hypertarget{the-basic-pattern}{%
\section{The Basic Pattern}\label{the-basic-pattern}}

The Unittest framework works as follows:

\textbf{Choose} on a method or class that you want to test.

\textbf{Create a class} that is a subclass of
\texttt{unittest.TestCase}.

In that class \textbf{write methods} that are designed to test the
behavior of methods in the code you want to test.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  These \textbf{test methods} focus on one behavior of one method (or
  function).
\item
  There can be \textbf{many test methods} for each target method.
\item
  Each test method name must be prefixed by \textbf{\texttt{test\_}}.
\item
  Tests are executing in alphabetical order, so name them in the order
  you want them executed.
\item
  Each test makes use of an \textbf{assert method}. These methods
  typically compare \textbf{expected} with \textbf{actual} methods and
  return \texttt{False} if they don't match and \texttt{True} if they
  do.
\item
  You always want tests to pass, so if you want to test if something
  breaks, you return \texttt{True} for a \texttt{False} condition.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Run} the script and see the results.

\textbf{Update} the script as you create new methods or refactor
existing ones.

\hypertarget{assert-methods}{%
\section{Assert Methods}\label{assert-methods}}
