\hypertarget{nb-control-structures-and-functions}{%
\chapter{NB: Control Structures and
Functions}\label{nb-control-structures-and-functions}}

\hypertarget{ifelse-statements}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{if}/\texttt{else}
Statements}{if/else Statements}}\label{ifelse-statements}}

You've seen this in Python.

They work the same way in both languages.

Here's their syntax in R.

\begin{verbatim}
if(<condition>) {
        ## do something
} 

if(<condition>) {
        ## do something
} 
else {
        ## do something else
}

if(<condition1>) {
        ## do something
} else if(<condition2>)  {
        ## do something different
} else {
        ## do something different
}
\end{verbatim}

Generate a uniform random number:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{x }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{runif}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{) }\CommentTok{\# From the Uniform Distribution}

\ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{(x }\SpecialCharTok{\textgreater{}} \DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{) \{}
\NormalTok{  y }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \DecValTok{10}
\NormalTok{\} }\ControlFlowTok{else}\NormalTok{ \{}
\NormalTok{  y }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \DecValTok{0}
\NormalTok{\}}

\NormalTok{x}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 1.356186
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{y}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 0
\end{verbatim}

You assign an \texttt{if} statement to a variable.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{z }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{(x }\SpecialCharTok{\textgreater{}} \DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{) \{}
  \DecValTok{10}
\NormalTok{\} }\ControlFlowTok{else}\NormalTok{ \{ }
  \DecValTok{0}
\NormalTok{\}}

\NormalTok{z}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 0
\end{verbatim}

You can stack \texttt{if} blocks, too.

\begin{verbatim}
if(<condition1>) {

}

if(<condition2>) {

}
\end{verbatim}

\hypertarget{control-structures}{%
\section{Control Structures}\label{control-structures}}

\hypertarget{for-loops}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{for}
Loops}{for Loops}}\label{for-loops}}

For loops are straight-forward. The take an interator variable, e.g.
\texttt{i}, and assign it successive values from a sequence or vector.

For loops are often used to iteratE over the elements of an object
(list, vector, etc.).

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{(i }\ControlFlowTok{in} \DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{) \{}
  \FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(i)}
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 1
[1] 2
[1] 3
[1] 4
[1] 5
[1] 6
[1] 7
[1] 8
[1] 9
[1] 10
\end{verbatim}

According to Hadley Wickham, loops are pretty much the only looping
construct that you will need in R.

The following three loops all have the same behavior.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{x }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"a"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"b"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"c"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"d"}\NormalTok{)}
\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ (i }\ControlFlowTok{in} \DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{) \{}
  \CommentTok{\# Print out each element of \textquotesingle{}x\textquotesingle{}}
  \FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(x[i])  }
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "a"
[1] "b"
[1] "c"
[1] "d"
\end{verbatim}

\hypertarget{seq_along}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{seq\_along()}}{seq\_along()}}\label{seq_along}}

The \texttt{seq\_along()} function is commonly used in conjunction with
for loops in order to generate an integer sequence based on the length
of an object (in this case, the object x).

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{x}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "a" "b" "c" "d"
\end{verbatim}

Generate a sequence based on length of `x':

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{(i }\ControlFlowTok{in} \FunctionTok{seq\_along}\NormalTok{(x)) \{   }
  \FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(x[i])}
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "a"
[1] "b"
[1] "c"
[1] "d"
\end{verbatim}

It is not necessary to use an index-type variable.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{(letter }\ControlFlowTok{in}\NormalTok{ x) \{}
  \FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(letter)}
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "a"
[1] "b"
[1] "c"
[1] "d"
\end{verbatim}

For one line loops, the curly braces are not strictly necessary.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{(i }\ControlFlowTok{in} \DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{) }\FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(x[i])}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "a"
[1] "b"
[1] "c"
[1] "d"
\end{verbatim}

\hypertarget{nested-for-loops}{%
\subsection{\texorpdfstring{Nested \texttt{for}
loops}{Nested for loops}}\label{nested-for-loops}}

Dor loops can be nested inside of each other.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{x }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{matrix}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{6}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{)}
\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{(i }\ControlFlowTok{in} \FunctionTok{seq\_len}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{nrow}\NormalTok{(x))) \{}
  \ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{(j }\ControlFlowTok{in} \FunctionTok{seq\_len}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{ncol}\NormalTok{(x))) \{}
    \FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(x[i, j])}
\NormalTok{  \}   }
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 1
[1] 3
[1] 5
[1] 2
[1] 4
[1] 6
\end{verbatim}

Nested loops are used to generate multidimensional or hierarchical data
structures (e.g.~matrices, lists).

\hypertarget{while-loops}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{while}
Loops}{while Loops}}\label{while-loops}}

As with Python, while loops start with a condition. It loops while the
condition is true and stops when it is false.

Remembe, while loops can go on forever is the truth condition is never
met.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{count }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \DecValTok{0}
\ControlFlowTok{while}\NormalTok{(count }\SpecialCharTok{\textless{}} \DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{) \{}
  \FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(count)}
\NormalTok{  count }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ count }\SpecialCharTok{+} \DecValTok{1}
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 0
[1] 1
[1] 2
[1] 3
[1] 4
[1] 5
[1] 6
[1] 7
[1] 8
[1] 9
\end{verbatim}

\hypertarget{repeat-loops}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{repeat}
Loops}{repeat Loops}}\label{repeat-loops}}

\texttt{repeat} loops are using by R. They initiate an infinite loop
right from the start.

The only way to exit a repeat loop is to call break on an internal
condition.

\hypertarget{next-and-break}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{next} and
\texttt{break}}{next and break}}\label{next-and-break}}

next is used to skip an iteration of a loop. Same as Python
\texttt{continue}.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ (i }\ControlFlowTok{in} \DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{100}\NormalTok{) \{}
  \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ (i }\SpecialCharTok{\textless{}=} \DecValTok{20}\NormalTok{) \{}
    \CommentTok{\# Skip the first 20 iterations}
    \ControlFlowTok{next}                
\NormalTok{  \}      }\CommentTok{\# Do something here}
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\texttt{break} is used to exit a loop immediately.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ (i }\ControlFlowTok{in} \DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{100}\NormalTok{) \{}
  \FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(i)}
  \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ (i }\SpecialCharTok{\textgreater{}} \DecValTok{20}\NormalTok{) \{}
    \CommentTok{\# Stop loop after 20 iterations}
    \ControlFlowTok{break}  
\NormalTok{  \}     }
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 1
[1] 2
[1] 3
[1] 4
[1] 5
[1] 6
[1] 7
[1] 8
[1] 9
[1] 10
[1] 11
[1] 12
[1] 13
[1] 14
[1] 15
[1] 16
[1] 17
[1] 18
[1] 19
[1] 20
[1] 21
\end{verbatim}

\hypertarget{functions}{%
\section{Functions}\label{functions}}

Define some data

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{x }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \DecValTok{5}                
\NormalTok{xx }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{6}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{7}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{8}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{11}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Now, define a function that does the following: - takes a value, vector
of values as inputs - normalizes the value against the vector by
subtracting the vector mean from value, and dividing by vector standard
deviation.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{compute\_zscore }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \ControlFlowTok{function}\NormalTok{(val, vec) \{}
\NormalTok{  z }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ (val }\SpecialCharTok{{-}} \FunctionTok{mean}\NormalTok{(vec)) }\SpecialCharTok{/} \FunctionTok{sd}\NormalTok{(vec)}
\NormalTok{\}}

\FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{compute\_zscore}\NormalTok{(x, xx))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] -0.4244764
\end{verbatim}

If vector contains identical values, \texttt{sd} is zero, and so the
z-score is undefined.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{compute\_zscore}\NormalTok{(x, }\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] Inf
\end{verbatim}

If vector contains missing values, the result will be \texttt{NA}.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{xx\_na }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\ConstantTok{NA}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{) }
\FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{compute\_zscore}\NormalTok{(x, xx\_na))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] NA
\end{verbatim}

\hypertarget{using-conditions-in-functions}{%
\section{Using conditions in
functions}\label{using-conditions-in-functions}}

A function returns 1 if passed value is odd, 0 if even

\hypertarget{is-mod-operator-returns-remainder}{%
\section{\%\% is mod operator (returns
remainder)}\label{is-mod-operator-returns-remainder}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{is\_odd }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \ControlFlowTok{function}\NormalTok{(x)\{ }\ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ (x }\SpecialCharTok{\%\%} \DecValTok{2} \SpecialCharTok{==} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{) \{ }
    \FunctionTok{return}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{) }
\NormalTok{  \} }\ControlFlowTok{else}\NormalTok{ \{ }
    \FunctionTok{return}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{  \} }
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Call to test some cases:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{is\_odd}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{4}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 0
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{is\_odd}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 1
\end{verbatim}

Function arguments can use default values:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{threshold\_vals }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \ControlFlowTok{function}\NormalTok{(p, }\AttributeTok{thresh =} \FloatTok{0.5}\NormalTok{) \{}
  \CommentTok{\# for each element in p, returns TRUE if value \textgreater{} thresh, else FALSE}
\NormalTok{  p }\SpecialCharTok{\textgreater{}}\NormalTok{ thresh}
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{threshold\_vals}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\FloatTok{0.6}\NormalTok{, }\FloatTok{0.4}\NormalTok{, }\FloatTok{0.1}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1]  TRUE FALSE FALSE  TRUE
\end{verbatim}

Now, pass a threshhold:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{threshold\_vals}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\FloatTok{0.6}\NormalTok{, }\FloatTok{0.4}\NormalTok{, }\FloatTok{0.1}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{), }\FloatTok{0.7}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE
\end{verbatim}

Assert important preconditions

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{add\_vectors }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \ControlFlowTok{function}\NormalTok{(x, y) \{}
  \CommentTok{\# assert the lengths of vectors x and y match}
  \CommentTok{\# if they do, sum elementwise, else throw error with stop()}

  \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ (}\FunctionTok{length}\NormalTok{(x) }\SpecialCharTok{!=} \FunctionTok{length}\NormalTok{(y)) \{}
    \FunctionTok{stop}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"x and y must be the same length"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{call. =} \ConstantTok{FALSE}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{  \}}
\NormalTok{  x }\SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ y}
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{add\_vectors}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{), }\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 4 5 6
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{add\_vectors}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{), }\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{)) }\CommentTok{\# breaks}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{scoping-rules}{%
\section{Scoping Rules}\label{scoping-rules}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{z }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \DecValTok{4}
\NormalTok{test\_fcn }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \ControlFlowTok{function}\NormalTok{(x) \{}
\NormalTok{  x}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\NormalTok{z}
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Now look at this:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{test\_fcn}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 16
\end{verbatim}

If \texttt{z} isn't defined in the function, how does this work?

R's scoping rules are similar to Python's.

Since \texttt{z} isn't in the function, \textbf{R looks in the
function's environment} for it.

For more on scoping rules, see
\href{https://bookdown.org/rdpeng/rprogdatascience/scoping-rules-of-r.html}{Chapter
15: Scoping Rules of R} in Peng's \emph{R Programming For Data Science}.

\hypertarget{static-weirdness-explained}{%
\section{Static Weirdness Explained}\label{static-weirdness-explained}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{class}\NormalTok{ Foo():}
    
\NormalTok{    my\_list }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ []    }\CommentTok{\# Lists are mutable}
\NormalTok{    my\_int }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{1}      \CommentTok{\# Integers are not}
\NormalTok{    my\_tuple }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ ()   }\CommentTok{\# Tuples are not}
    
    \KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ mutate\_things(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{):}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.my\_list.append(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{) }\CommentTok{\# MUTATING THE OBJECT DEFINE AT THE CLASS LEVEL}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.my\_int }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{2}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.my\_tuple }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ (}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{)}
                
    \KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ change\_things(}\VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{):}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.my\_list }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ [}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{] }\CommentTok{\# REMOVING THE CONNECTION TO THE CLASS LEVEL}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.my\_int }\OperatorTok{=} \DecValTok{2}
        \VariableTok{self}\NormalTok{.my\_tuple }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ (}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{)}
        
        \CommentTok{\# If you mutate a mutable, then it will change}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\KeywordTok{def}\NormalTok{ foo\_state(foo): }
    \KeywordTok{global}\NormalTok{ Foo}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Class state:"}\NormalTok{, Foo.my\_list, Foo.my\_int, Foo.my\_tuple)}
    \BuiltInTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"Object state:"}\NormalTok{, foo.my\_list, foo.my\_int, foo.my\_tuple)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{foo1 }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ Foo()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{foo1.mutate\_things()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{foo\_state(foo1)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
Class state: [1] 1 ()
Object state: [1] 2 (1, 3)
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{foo1.change\_things()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{foo\_state(foo1)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
Class state: [1] 1 ()
Object state: [1] 2 (1, 3)
\end{verbatim}

\section{Narrow vs Wide Tables}\label{narrow-vs-wide-tables}}

\NormalTok{pets }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.Series(}\StringTok{"cat dog ferret snake turtle parraot"}\NormalTok{.split()).sample(}\DecValTok{1000}\NormalTok{, replace}\OperatorTok{=}\VariableTok{True}\NormalTok{).to\_list()}
\NormalTok{people }\OperatorTok{=}\NormalTok{ pd.Series(}\StringTok{"A B C D E F G"}\NormalTok{.split()).sample(}\DecValTok{1000}\NormalTok{, replace}\OperatorTok{=}\VariableTok{True}\NormalTok{).to\_list()   }

\hypertarget{nb-introducing-tibbles}{%
\chapter{NB: Introducing Tibbles}\label{nb-introducing-tibbles}}

\begin{quote}

\hypertarget{the-tidyverse}{%
\section{The Tidyverse}\label{the-tidyverse}}

Tidyverse is a collection of essential R packages for data science.

The packages included in the Tidyverse are designed to support the
pipeline of activities associated with data science, such as filtering,
transforming, visualizing, etc.

\includegraphics{notebooks/M11_RDplyr/images/paste-EE0D9577.png}

Tidyverse was created by \textbf{Hadley Wickham} and his team with the
aim of providing all these utilities to clean and work with data.

Here's a graphic of the packages associated with the TV:

\includegraphics{notebooks/M11_RDplyr/images/paste-32BD3A67.png}

We are going to focus on \texttt{dplyr} today and \texttt{ggplot}
tomorrow.

\hypertarget{dplyr}{%
\section{Dplyr}\label{dplyr}}

Dplyr introduces \textbf{new set of functions} that make working with
data more intuitive.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  It does this by introducing a set of functions that work together well
  to produce pipelines of actions.
\end{itemize}

But as important, it introduces a \textbf{vocabulary} for talking about
data.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  This makes it possible to imagine solutions verbally, and then to
  implement them in code.
\end{itemize}

To use the TV, we usually import everything:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{library}\NormalTok{(tidyverse)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
-- Attaching packages --------------------------------------- tidyverse 1.3.2 --
v ggplot2 3.3.5     v purrr   1.0.1
v tibble  3.2.1     v dplyr   1.1.1
v tidyr   1.2.1     v stringr 1.5.0
v readr   2.1.3     v forcats 1.0.0
-- Conflicts ------------------------------------------ tidyverse_conflicts() --
x dplyr::filter() masks stats::filter()
x dplyr::lag()    masks stats::lag()
\end{verbatim}

\hypertarget{piping-with}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{Piping with
\texttt{\%\textgreater{}\%}}{Piping with \%\textgreater\%}}\label{piping-with}}

Just a quick note about this \textbf{odd looking} operator that you will
start to see.

One of the key elements of the TV is the use of \textbf{piping}, or the
ability of to pass the return values of one function to another, with
without have to nest functions.

For example, instead of something like this:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{a }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \StringTok{"Hello"}
\NormalTok{b }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \StringTok{"World"}

\NormalTok{var1 }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(a, b)}
\NormalTok{var2 }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{paste}\NormalTok{(var1)}
\FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(var2)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "Hello" "World"
\end{verbatim}

Or this:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{paste}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(a,b)))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "Hello" "World"
\end{verbatim}

We can do:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(a, b) }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
  \FunctionTok{paste}\NormalTok{() }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
  \FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "Hello" "World"
\end{verbatim}

Although the last pattern is longer than the preceding, it is much
easier to read and write, especially when we are working with several
connected functions.

This is similar to \textbf{method chaining} in Python, but is more
pervasive.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  In Python you can do it with individual objects that return themselves
  (as it were).
\item
  In TV, you can apply it to \textbf{any two methods} so long as it
  makes sense to pass the output of as the input of another.
\item
  Basically, the output of one function becomes the first argument of
  the following the \texttt{\%\textgreater{}\%}.
\end{itemize}

It is similar to the pipe operator \texttt{\textbar{}} in Unix shells.

\hypertarget{tibbles}{%
\chapter{Tibbles}\label{tibbles}}

Dplyr can work with different rectangular data structures:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Data frames
\item
  Tibbles
\item
  Data.tables (see
  \href{https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/data.table/vignettes/datatable-intro.html}{data.table})
\end{itemize}

The foundational data structure of the TV is the \textbf{tibble}.

Tibbles are data frames, but they tweak some older behaviors to make
your life a little easier.

To learn more about tibbles, check out the vignette:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{vignette}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"tibble"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
starting httpd help server ... done
\end{verbatim}

\hypertarget{creating-tibbles}{%
\section{Creating tibbles}\label{creating-tibbles}}

If you need to make a tibble ``by hand'', you can use \texttt{tibble()}
or \texttt{tribble()}.

\texttt{tibble()} works by assembling individual vectors,
\textbf{column-wise} operation:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{x }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{y }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"a"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"b"}\NormalTok{, }\StringTok{"h"}\NormalTok{)}
\FunctionTok{tibble}\NormalTok{(x, y)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
# A tibble: 3 x 2
      x y    
  <dbl> <chr>
1     1 a    
2     2 b    
3     5 h    
\end{verbatim}

You can also optionally name the inputs, provide data inline with
\texttt{c()}, and perform computation:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{tibble}\NormalTok{(}
  \AttributeTok{x1 =}\NormalTok{ x,}
  \AttributeTok{x2 =} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{15}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{25}\NormalTok{),}
  \AttributeTok{y =} \FunctionTok{sqrt}\NormalTok{(x1}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2} \SpecialCharTok{+}\NormalTok{ x2}\SpecialCharTok{\^{}}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
# A tibble: 3 x 3
     x1    x2     y
  <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
1     1    10  10.0
2     2    15  15.1
3     5    25  25.5
\end{verbatim}

Every column in a data frame or tibble must be same length, so you'll
get an error if the lengths are different:

As the error suggests, individual values will be recycled to the same
length as everything else:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{tibble}\NormalTok{(}
  \AttributeTok{x =} \DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{,}
  \AttributeTok{y =} \StringTok{"a"}\NormalTok{,}
  \AttributeTok{z =} \ConstantTok{TRUE}
\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
# A tibble: 5 x 3
      x y     z    
  <int> <chr> <lgl>
1     1 a     TRUE 
2     2 a     TRUE 
3     3 a     TRUE 
4     4 a     TRUE 
5     5 a     TRUE 
\end{verbatim}

\hypertarget{tribbles}{%
\section{Tribbles}\label{tribbles}}

Another way to create a tibble is with \texttt{tribble()}, which short
for \textbf{transposed tibble}.

\texttt{tribble()} is customized for data entry in code: \textbf{column
headings start with \texttt{\textasciitilde{}}} and \textbf{entries are
separated by commas}.

This makes it possible to lay out small amounts of data in an easy to
read form:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{tribble}\NormalTok{(}
  \SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\NormalTok{x, }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\NormalTok{y, }\SpecialCharTok{\textasciitilde{}}\NormalTok{z,}
  \StringTok{"a"}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{, }\FloatTok{3.6}\NormalTok{,}
  \StringTok{"b"}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\FloatTok{8.5}
\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
# A tibble: 2 x 3
  x         y     z
  <chr> <dbl> <dbl>
1 a         2   3.6
2 b         1   8.5
\end{verbatim}

Finally, if you have a regular \texttt{data\ frame} you can turn it into
to a tibble with \texttt{as\_tibble()}:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{as\_tibble}\NormalTok{(mtcars)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
# A tibble: 32 x 11
     mpg   cyl  disp    hp  drat    wt  qsec    vs    am  gear  carb
   <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
 1  21       6  160    110  3.9   2.62  16.5     0     1     4     4
 2  21       6  160    110  3.9   2.88  17.0     0     1     4     4
 3  22.8     4  108     93  3.85  2.32  18.6     1     1     4     1
 4  21.4     6  258    110  3.08  3.22  19.4     1     0     3     1
 5  18.7     8  360    175  3.15  3.44  17.0     0     0     3     2
 6  18.1     6  225    105  2.76  3.46  20.2     1     0     3     1
 7  14.3     8  360    245  3.21  3.57  15.8     0     0     3     4
 8  24.4     4  147.    62  3.69  3.19  20       1     0     4     2
 9  22.8     4  141.    95  3.92  3.15  22.9     1     0     4     2
10  19.2     6  168.   123  3.92  3.44  18.3     1     0     4     4
# i 22 more rows
\end{verbatim}

The inverse of \texttt{as\_tibble()} is \texttt{as.data.frame()}; it
converts a tibble back into a regular \texttt{data.frame}.

\hypertarget{non-syntactic-names}{%
\section{Non-syntactic names}\label{non-syntactic-names}}

It's possible for a tibble to have column names that are not valid R
variable names, names that are \textbf{non-syntactic}.

For example, the variables might not start with a letter or they might
contain unusual characters like a space.

To refer to these variables, you need to surround them with backticks,
\texttt{\textasciigrave{}}:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{tb }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{tibble}\NormalTok{(}
  \StringTok{\textasciigrave{}}\AttributeTok{:)}\StringTok{\textasciigrave{}} \OtherTok{=} \StringTok{"smile"}\NormalTok{, }
  \StringTok{\textasciigrave{}}\AttributeTok{ }\StringTok{\textasciigrave{}} \OtherTok{=} \StringTok{"space"}\NormalTok{,}
  \StringTok{\textasciigrave{}}\AttributeTok{2000}\StringTok{\textasciigrave{}} \OtherTok{=} \StringTok{"number"}
\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{tb}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
# A tibble: 1 x 3
  `:)`  ` `   `2000`
  <chr> <chr> <chr> 
1 smile space number
\end{verbatim}

You'll also need the backticks when working with these variables in
other packages, like ggplot2, dplyr, and tidyr.

\hypertarget{tibbles-vs.-data.frame}{%
\chapter{Tibbles vs.~data.frame}\label{tibbles-vs.-data.frame}}

There are two main differences in the usage of a tibble vs.~a classic
\texttt{dat\ frame}:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{printing} and \textbf{subsetting}.
\end{itemize}

If these difference cause problems when working with older packages, you
can turn a tibble back to a regular data frame with
\texttt{as.data.frame()}.

\hypertarget{printing}{%
\section{Printing}\label{printing}}

The print method:

\begin{itemize}
\item
  Only the first 10 rows
\item
  All the columns that fit on screen.
\end{itemize}

This makes it much easier to work with large data.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{tibble}\NormalTok{(}
  \AttributeTok{a =}\NormalTok{ lubridate}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{now}\NormalTok{() }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{runif}\NormalTok{(}\FloatTok{1e3}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{*} \DecValTok{86400}\NormalTok{,}
  \AttributeTok{b =}\NormalTok{ lubridate}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{today}\NormalTok{() }\SpecialCharTok{+} \FunctionTok{runif}\NormalTok{(}\FloatTok{1e3}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{*} \DecValTok{30}\NormalTok{,}
  \AttributeTok{c =} \DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{:}\FloatTok{1e3}\NormalTok{,}
  \AttributeTok{d =} \FunctionTok{runif}\NormalTok{(}\FloatTok{1e3}\NormalTok{),}
  \AttributeTok{e =} \FunctionTok{sample}\NormalTok{(letters, }\FloatTok{1e3}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{replace =} \ConstantTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
# A tibble: 1,000 x 5
   a                   b              c      d e    
   <dttm>              <date>     <int>  <dbl> <chr>
 1 2023-06-19 18:40:15 2023-06-21     1 0.150  j    
 2 2023-06-19 13:10:40 2023-06-25     2 0.556  j    
 3 2023-06-19 10:53:19 2023-06-20     3 0.895  l    
 4 2023-06-20 07:11:06 2023-06-25     4 0.295  q    
 5 2023-06-20 01:56:41 2023-06-25     5 0.658  n    
 6 2023-06-19 13:22:02 2023-07-07     6 0.635  n    
 7 2023-06-20 10:19:22 2023-06-21     7 0.0475 q    
 8 2023-06-20 00:48:16 2023-07-07     8 0.620  i    
 9 2023-06-19 22:28:22 2023-07-18     9 0.906  p    
10 2023-06-19 18:35:02 2023-06-30    10 0.611  l    
# i 990 more rows
\end{verbatim}

Where possible, \textbf{tibbles also use color} to draw your eye to
important differences.

One of the most important distinctions is between the string
\texttt{"NA"} and the missing value, \texttt{NA}:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{tibble}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{x =} \FunctionTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"NA"}\NormalTok{, }\ConstantTok{NA}\NormalTok{))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
# A tibble: 2 x 1
  x    
  <chr>
1 NA   
2 <NA> 
\end{verbatim}

Tibbles are designed to avoid overwhelming your console when you print
large data frames.

But \textbf{sometimes you need more output} than the default display.

There are a few options that can help.

First, you can explicitly \texttt{print()} the data frame and control
the number of rows (\texttt{n}) and the \texttt{width} of the display.
\texttt{width\ =\ Inf} will display all columns:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{library}\NormalTok{(nycflights13)}
\NormalTok{flights }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
  \FunctionTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{n =} \DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{width =} \ConstantTok{Inf}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
# A tibble: 336,776 x 19
    year month   day dep_time sched_dep_time dep_delay arr_time sched_arr_time

10  2013     1     1      558            600        -2      753            745

You can also \textbf{control the default print behavior} by setting
options:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \texttt{options(tibble.print\_max\ =\ n,\ tibble.print\_min\ =\ m)}:
  if more than \texttt{n} rows, print only \texttt{m} rows.
\item
  Use \texttt{options(tibble.print\_min\ =\ Inf)} to always show all
  rows.
\item
  Use \texttt{options(tibble.width\ =\ Inf)} to always print all
  columns, regardless of the width of the screen.
\end{itemize}

You can see a complete list of options by looking at the package help
with \texttt{package?tibble}.

\hypertarget{using-view}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{Using
\texttt{View()}}{Using View()}}\label{using-view}}

A final option is to use RStudio's built-in data viewer to get a
scrollable view of the complete dataset. This is also often useful at
the end of a long chain of manipulations.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{flights }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
  \FunctionTok{View}\NormalTok{()}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{extracting-variables}{%
\section{Extracting variables}\label{extracting-variables}}

So far all the tools you've learned have worked with complete data
frames.

If you want to pull out a single variable, you can use
\texttt{dplyr::pull()}:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{tb }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{tibble}\NormalTok{(}
  \AttributeTok{id =}\NormalTok{ LETTERS[}\DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{],}
  \AttributeTok{x1  =} \DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{,}
  \AttributeTok{y1  =} \DecValTok{6}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{10}
\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{tb }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}  
  \FunctionTok{pull}\NormalTok{(x1) }\CommentTok{\# by name}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 1 2 3 4 5
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{tb }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}  
  \FunctionTok{pull}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{)  }\CommentTok{\# by position}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "A" "B" "C" "D" "E"
\end{verbatim}

\texttt{pull()} also takes an optional \texttt{name} argument that
specifies the column to be used as names for a named vector, which
you'll learn about in \textbf{?@sec-vectors}.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{tb }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}  
  \FunctionTok{pull}\NormalTok{(x1, }\AttributeTok{name =}\NormalTok{ id)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
A B C D E 
1 2 3 4 5 
\end{verbatim}

You can also use the base R tools \texttt{\$} and \texttt{{[}{[}}.
\texttt{{[}{[}} can extract by name or position; \texttt{\$} only
extracts by name but is a little less typing.

Extract by name:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{tb}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{x1}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 1 2 3 4 5
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{tb[[}\StringTok{"x1"}\NormalTok{]]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 1 2 3 4 5
\end{verbatim}

Extract by position:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{tb[[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{]]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "A" "B" "C" "D" "E"
\end{verbatim}

Compared to a \texttt{data\ frame}, \textbf{tibbles are more strict}:
they never do partial matching, and they will generate a warning if the
column you are trying to access does not exist.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\# Tibbles complain a lot:}
\NormalTok{tb}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{x}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
Warning: Unknown or uninitialised column: `x`.
\end{verbatim}

\begin{verbatim}
NULL
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{tb}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{z}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
Warning: Unknown or uninitialised column: `z`.
\end{verbatim}

\begin{verbatim}
NULL
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\# Data frame use partial matching and don\textquotesingle{}t complain if a column doesn\textquotesingle{}t exist}
\NormalTok{df }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{as.data.frame}\NormalTok{(tb)}
\NormalTok{df}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{x}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 1 2 3 4 5
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{df}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{z}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
NULL
\end{verbatim}

For this reason we sometimes joke that \textbf{tibbles are lazy and
surly}: they do less and complain more.

\hypertarget{subsetting}{%
\section{Subsetting}\label{subsetting}}

Lastly, there are some important differences when using \texttt{{[}}.

With \texttt{data.frame}s, \texttt{{[}} sometimes returns a
\texttt{data.frame}, and sometimes returns a vector.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  This is a common source of bugs.
\end{itemize}

With tibbles, \textbf{\texttt{{[}} always returns another tibble}.

\begin{itemize}
\item
  This can sometimes cause problems when working with older code.
\item
  If you hit one of those functions, just use \texttt{as.data.frame()}
  to turn your tibble back to a \texttt{data.frame}.
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{nb-the-dplyr-package}{%
\chapter{\texorpdfstring{NB: The \texttt{dplyr}
package}{NB: The dplyr package}}\label{nb-the-dplyr-package}}

\begin{quote}
Based on \href{https://bookdown.org/rdpeng/rprogdatascience/}{Peng 2022}
\end{quote}

The \texttt{dplyr} package was developed by Hadley Wickham of RStudio
and is an optimized and distilled version of his \texttt{plyr} package.

\begin{quote}
\texttt{plyr} is an attempt to organize much of the functionality of the
\texttt{*apply} family of methods in R. Some of these methods are
superseded by dplyr and plyr, but
\href{https://stackoverflow.com/questions/3505701/grouping-functions-tapply-by-aggregate-and-the-apply-family}{they
remain useful}.
\end{quote}

The \texttt{dplyr} package does not provide any ``new'' functionality to
R per se, in the sense that everything \texttt{dplyr} does could already
be done with base R, but it \emph{greatly} simplifies existing
functionality in R.

One important contribution of the \texttt{dplyr} package is that it
provides a ``grammar'' (in particular, verbs) for data manipulation and
for operating on data frames. With this grammar, you can sensibly
communicate what it is that you are doing to a data frame that other
people can understand (assuming they also know the grammar). This is
useful because it provides an abstraction for data manipulation that
previously did not exist. Another useful contribution is that the
\texttt{dplyr} functions are \textbf{very} fast, as many key operations
are coded in C++.

\hypertarget{dplyr-grammar}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{dplyr}
Grammar}{dplyr Grammar}}\label{dplyr-grammar}}

Some of the key ``verbs'' provided by the \texttt{dplyr} package are

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \texttt{select}: return a subset of the columns of a data frame, using
  a flexible notation
\item
  \texttt{filter}: extract a subset of rows from a data frame based on
  logical conditions
\item
  \texttt{arrange}: reorder rows of a data frame
\item
  \texttt{rename}: rename variables in a data frame
\item
  \texttt{mutate}: add new variables/columns or transform existing
  variables
\item
  \texttt{summarise} / \texttt{summarize}: generate summary statistics
  of different variables in the data frame, possibly within strata
\item
  \texttt{\%\textgreater{}\%}: the ``pipe'' operator is used to connect
  multiple verb actions together into a pipeline
\end{itemize}

The \texttt{dplyr} package as a number of its own data types that it
takes advantage of. For example, there is a handy \texttt{print} method
that prevents you from printing a lot of data to the console. Most of
the time, these additional data types are transparent to the user and do
not need to be worried about.

\hypertarget{common-dplyr-function-properties}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{Common \texttt{dplyr} Function
Properties}{Common dplyr Function Properties}}\label{common-dplyr-function-properties}}

All of the functions that we will discuss in this Chapter will have a
few common characteristics. In particular,

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\item
  The first argument is a data frame.
\item
  The subsequent arguments describe what to do with the data frame
  specified in the first argument, and you can refer to columns in the
  data frame directly without using the \$ operator (just use the column
  names).
\item
  The return result of a function is a new data frame.
\item
  Data frames must be properly formatted and annotated for this to all
  be useful. In particular, the data must be
  \href{http://www.jstatsoft.org/v59/i10/paper}{tidy}. In short, there
  should be one observation per row, and each column should represent a
  feature or characteristic of that observation.
\end{enumerate}

\hypertarget{installing-the-dplyr-package}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{Installing the \texttt{dplyr}
package}{Installing the dplyr package}}\label{installing-the-dplyr-package}}

The \texttt{dplyr} package can be installed from CRAN or from GitHub
using the \texttt{devtools} package and the \texttt{install\_github()}
function. The GitHub repository will usually contain the latest updates
to the package and the development version.

To install from CRAN, just run

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{install.packages}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"dplyr"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

To install from GitHub you can run

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{install\_github}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"hadley/dplyr"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

After installing the package it is important that you load it into your
R session with the \texttt{library()} function.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{library}\NormalTok{(dplyr)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}

Attaching package: 'dplyr'
\end{verbatim}

\begin{verbatim}
The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':

    filter, lag
\end{verbatim}

\begin{verbatim}
The following objects are masked from 'package:base':

    intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
\end{verbatim}

You may get some warnings when the package is loaded because there are
functions in the \texttt{dplyr} package that have the same name as
functions in other packages. For now you can ignore the warnings.

\hypertarget{getting-a-dataset}{%
\section{Getting a dataset}\label{getting-a-dataset}}

Let's use a dataset containing air pollution and temperature data for
the
\href{http://www.biostat.jhsph.edu/~rpeng/leanpub/rprog/chicago_data.zip}{city
of Chicago} in the U.S.

\begin{quote}
You will find the data in the directory for this module.
\end{quote}

Load the data into R using the \texttt{readRDS()} function.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{chicago }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{readRDS}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"chicago.rds"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

You can see some basic characteristics of the dataset with the
\texttt{dim()} and \texttt{str()} functions.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{dim}\NormalTok{(chicago)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] 6940    8
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{str}\NormalTok{(chicago)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
'data.frame':   6940 obs. of  8 variables:
 $ city      : chr  "chic" "chic" "chic" "chic" ...
 $ tmpd      : num  31.5 33 33 29 32 40 34.5 29 26.5 32.5 ...
 $ dptp      : num  31.5 29.9 27.4 28.6 28.9 ...
 $ date      : Date, format: "1987-01-01" "1987-01-02" ...

\hypertarget{select}{%
\chapter{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{select()}}{select()}}\label{select}}

We use the \texttt{select()} function to \textbf{select columns you want
to focus on}.

Suppose we wanted to take the first 3 columns only.

There are a few ways to do this.

We could for example use numerical indices.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{names}\NormalTok{(chicago)[}\DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{]}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
[1] "city" "tmpd" "dptp"
\end{verbatim}

But we can also use the names directly.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{chicago }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
  \FunctionTok{select}\NormalTok{(city}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{dptp)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Note the use of \texttt{:} inside the \texttt{select()} --- you can use
it to specify a range of variable names.

You can also \emph{omit} variables using the \texttt{select()} function
by using \textbf{the negative sign}. With \texttt{select()} you can do

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{select}\NormalTok{(chicago, }\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{(city}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{dptp))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

This indicates that we should include every variable \emph{except} the
variables \texttt{city} through \texttt{dptp}.

The equivalent code in base R would be

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{i }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{match}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"city"}\NormalTok{, }\FunctionTok{names}\NormalTok{(chicago))}
\NormalTok{j }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{match}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"dptp"}\NormalTok{, }\FunctionTok{names}\NormalTok{(chicago))}
\FunctionTok{head}\NormalTok{(chicago[, }\SpecialCharTok{{-}}\NormalTok{(i}\SpecialCharTok{:}\NormalTok{j)])}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Not super intuitive, right?

The \texttt{select()} function also allows a special syntax that allows
you to specify \textbf{variable names based on patterns}.

So, for example, if you wanted to keep every variable that ends with a
``2'', we could do

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{chicago }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
  \FunctionTok{select}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{ends\_with}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"2"}\NormalTok{))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{filter}{%
\chapter{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{filter()}}{filter()}}\label{filter}}

The \texttt{filter()} function extracts \textbf{subsets of rows} from a
data frame.

\begin{quote}
\texttt{select()} is a \textbf{column-wise} operation, \texttt{filter()}
is \textbf{row-wise}.
\end{quote}

This function is similar to the existing \texttt{subset()} function in R
but is quite a bit faster.

Suppose we wanted to extract the rows of the \texttt{chicago} data frame
where \textbf{the levels of PM2.5 are greater than 30} (which is a
reasonably high level), we could do

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{chicago }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
  \FunctionTok{filter}\NormalTok{(pm25tmean2 }\SpecialCharTok{\textgreater{}} \DecValTok{30}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

We can place an arbitrarily complex logical sequence inside of
\texttt{filter()}, so we could for example extract the rows where PM2.5
is greater than 30 \emph{and} temperature is greater than 80 degrees
Fahrenheit.

\hypertarget{arrange}{%
\chapter{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{arrange()}}{arrange()}}\label{arrange}}

Use \texttt{arrange()} to \textbf{reorder rows} of a data frame
according to one or more of the \textbf{columns}.

\begin{quote}
This normally called \textbf{sorting}, but this word is already used in
R.
\end{quote}

Reordering rows of a data frame (while preserving corresponding order of
other columns) is normally a pain to do in R.

The \texttt{arrange()} function simplifies the process quite a bit.

Here we order the rows of the data frame by date in ascending order:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{chicago\_by\_date }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ chicago }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
  \FunctionTok{arrange}\NormalTok{(date)}
\NormalTok{chicago\_by\_date}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{rename}{%
\chapter{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{rename()}}{rename()}}\label{rename}}

Renaming a variable in a data frame in R is surprisingly hard to do!

The \texttt{rename()} function is designed to make this process easier.

Here we the names of the first five variables in the \texttt{chicago}
data frame.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{head}\NormalTok{(chicago[, }\DecValTok{1}\SpecialCharTok{:}\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{], }\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
  city tmpd   dptp       date pm25tmean2
1 chic 31.5 31.500 1987-01-01         NA
2 chic 33.0 29.875 1987-01-02         NA
3 chic 33.0 27.375 1987-01-03         NA
\end{verbatim}

The \texttt{dptp} column is supposed to represent the dew point
temperature and the \texttt{pm25tmean2} column provides the PM2.5 data.

However, these names are awkward and should be renamed to something more
sensible.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{chicago }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ chicago }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
  \FunctionTok{rename}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{dewpoint =}\NormalTok{ dptp, }\AttributeTok{pm25 =}\NormalTok{ pm25tmean2)}
  
\NormalTok{chicago }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}  
  \FunctionTok{head}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
  city tmpd dewpoint       date pm25 pm10tmean2 o3tmean2 no2tmean2
1 chic 31.5   31.500 1987-01-01   NA   34.00000 4.250000  19.98810
2 chic 33.0   29.875 1987-01-02   NA         NA 3.304348  23.19099
3 chic 33.0   27.375 1987-01-03   NA   34.16667 3.333333  23.81548
\end{verbatim}

The syntax inside the \texttt{rename()} function is to have the new name
on the left-hand side of the \texttt{=} sign and the old name on the
right-hand side.

I leave it as an exercise for the reader to figure how you do this in
base R without \texttt{dplyr}.

\hypertarget{mutate}{%
\chapter{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{mutate()}}{mutate()}}\label{mutate}}

The \texttt{mutate()} function creates new columns based on computations
usually involving the other columns.

For example, with air pollution data, \textbf{we often want to
\emph{detrend} the data by subtracting the mean from the data}.

That way we can look at whether a given day's air pollution level is
higher than or less than average (as opposed to looking at its absolute
level).

Here we create a \texttt{pm25detrend} variable that subtracts the mean
from the \texttt{pm25} variable.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{chicago }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ chicago }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
  \FunctionTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{pm25detrend =}\NormalTok{ pm25 }\SpecialCharTok{{-}} \FunctionTok{mean}\NormalTok{(pm25, }\AttributeTok{na.rm =} \ConstantTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{))}
\NormalTok{chicago }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
  \FunctionTok{head}\NormalTok{()}
\end{Highlighting}

\hypertarget{group_by}{%
\chapter{\texorpdfstring{\texttt{group\_by()}}{group\_by()}}\label{group_by}}

The \texttt{group\_by()} function is used to generate \textbf{summary or
aggregate statistics} from a data frame.

For example, in this air pollution dataset, you might want to know the
\textbf{average annual level of PM2.5}.

So \textbf{the stratum is the year}, which we can derive from the
\texttt{date} variable.

\textbf{In conjunction with the \texttt{group\_by()} function we often
use the \texttt{summarize()} function.} \textgreater{} Or
\texttt{summarise()} for some parts of the world.

The general operation here is a combination of \textbf{splitting} a
tabel into separate pieces defined by a variable or group of variables
(\texttt{group\_by()}), and then \textbf{applying} a summary function
across those subsets (\texttt{summarize()}), then \textbf{combining}
back into another table.

\begin{quote}
This pattern is called \textbf{split, apply, and combine}. It is a
fundamental pattern in data processing.
\end{quote}

First, we can create a \texttt{year} variable using
\texttt{as.POSIXlt()}.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{chicago }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ chicago }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
  \FunctionTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{year =} \FunctionTok{as.POSIXlt}\NormalTok{(date)}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{year }\SpecialCharTok{+} \DecValTok{1900}\NormalTok{)}
\FunctionTok{head}\NormalTok{(chicago)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
  city tmpd dewpoint       date pm25 pm10tmean2 o3tmean2 no2tmean2 pm25detrend
1 chic 31.5   31.500 1987-01-01   NA   34.00000 4.250000  19.98810          NA
2 chic 33.0   29.875 1987-01-02   NA         NA 3.304348  23.19099          NA
3 chic 33.0   27.375 1987-01-03   NA   34.16667 3.333333  23.81548          NA
4 chic 29.0   28.625 1987-01-04   NA   47.00000 4.375000  30.43452          NA
5 chic 32.0   28.875 1987-01-05   NA         NA 4.750000  30.33333          NA
6 chic 40.0   35.125 1987-01-06   NA   48.00000 5.833333  25.77233          NA
  year
1 1987
2 1987
3 1987
4 1987
5 1987
6 1987
\end{verbatim}

Now we can create a that computes summary statistics for each year in
the data frame with the \texttt{summarize()} function.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{years }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}}\NormalTok{ chicago }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
  \FunctionTok{group\_by}\NormalTok{(year) }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
  \FunctionTok{summarize}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{pm25 =} \FunctionTok{mean}\NormalTok{(pm25, }\AttributeTok{na.rm =} \ConstantTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{), }
          \AttributeTok{o3 =} \FunctionTok{max}\NormalTok{(o3tmean2, }\AttributeTok{na.rm =} \ConstantTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{), }
          \AttributeTok{no2 =} \FunctionTok{median}\NormalTok{(no2tmean2, }\AttributeTok{na.rm =} \ConstantTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{), }\AttributeTok{.groups =} \StringTok{"drop"}\NormalTok{)}
\FunctionTok{head}\NormalTok{(years)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
# A tibble: 6 x 4
   year  pm25    o3   no2
  <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
1  1987   NaN  63.0  23.5
2  1988   NaN  61.7  24.5
3  1989   NaN  59.7  26.1
4  1990   NaN  52.2  22.6
5  1991   NaN  63.1  21.4
6  1992   NaN  50.8  24.8
\end{verbatim}

Note in the process, we implicitly created separate data frame that
splits the original data frame by year, which is then passed to
\texttt{summarize()}.

\texttt{summarize()} then returns a data frame with columns for
\texttt{year} and the annual averages of \texttt{pm25}, \texttt{o3}, and
\texttt{no2}.

In a slightly more complicated example, we might want to know what are
the average levels of ozone (\texttt{o3}) and nitrogen dioxide
(\texttt{no2}) within quintiles of \texttt{pm25}.

A slicker way to do this would be through a regression model, but we can
actually do this quickly with \texttt{group\_by()} and
\texttt{summarize()}.

First, we can create a categorical variable of \texttt{pm25} divided
into quantiles.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{qq }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{quantile}\NormalTok{(chicago}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{pm25, }\FunctionTok{seq}\NormalTok{(}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{, }\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{, }\FloatTok{0.2}\NormalTok{), }\AttributeTok{na.rm =} \ConstantTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Then can group the data frame by the \texttt{pm25.quint} variable. and
compute the mean of \texttt{o3} and \texttt{no2} within quantiles of
\texttt{pm25}.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{chicago }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
  \FunctionTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{pm25.quint =} \FunctionTok{cut}\NormalTok{(pm25, qq)) }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
  \FunctionTok{group\_by}\NormalTok{(pm25.quint) }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
  \FunctionTok{summarize}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{o3 =} \FunctionTok{mean}\NormalTok{(o3tmean2, }\AttributeTok{na.rm =} \ConstantTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{), }
          \AttributeTok{no2 =} \FunctionTok{mean}\NormalTok{(no2tmean2, }\AttributeTok{na.rm =} \ConstantTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{),}
          \AttributeTok{.groups =} \StringTok{"drop"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
# A tibble: 6 x 3
  pm25.quint     o3   no2
  <fct>       <dbl> <dbl>
1 (1.7,8.7]    21.7  18.0
2 (8.7,12.4]   20.4  22.1
3 (12.4,16.7]  20.7  24.4
4 (16.7,22.6]  19.9  27.3
5 (22.6,61.5]  20.3  29.6
6 <NA>         18.8  25.8
\end{verbatim}

From the table, it seems there isn't a strong relationship between
\texttt{pm25} and \texttt{o3}, but there appears to be a positive
correlation between \texttt{pm25} and \texttt{no2}.

More sophisticated statistical modeling can help to provide precise
answers to these questions, but a simple application of \texttt{dplyr}
functions can often get you most of the way there.

Here is another example:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{chicago }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}  
  \FunctionTok{mutate}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{month =} \FunctionTok{as.POSIXlt}\NormalTok{(date)}\SpecialCharTok{$}\NormalTok{mon }\SpecialCharTok{+} \DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{) }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%} 
  \FunctionTok{group\_by}\NormalTok{(month) }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}                              \CommentTok{\# SPLIT}
  \FunctionTok{summarize}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{pm25 =} \FunctionTok{mean}\NormalTok{(pm25, }\AttributeTok{na.rm =} \ConstantTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{),       }\CommentTok{\# APPLY }
    \AttributeTok{o3 =} \FunctionTok{max}\NormalTok{(o3tmean2, }\AttributeTok{na.rm =} \ConstantTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{), }
    \AttributeTok{no2 =} \FunctionTok{median}\NormalTok{(no2tmean2, }\AttributeTok{na.rm =} \ConstantTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{),}
    \AttributeTok{.groups =} \StringTok{"drop"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
# A tibble: 12 x 4
   month  pm25    o3   no2
   <dbl> <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>
 1     1  17.8  28.2  25.4
 2     2  20.4  37.4  26.8

\hypertarget{summary-2}{%
\chapter{Summary}\label{summary-2}}

The \texttt{dplyr} package provides a concise set of operations for
managing data frames and tibbles.

It allows us to perform a number of complex operations in just a few
lines of code.

In particular, we can often conduct the beginnings of an exploratory
analysis with the powerful combination of \texttt{group\_by()} and
\texttt{summarize()}.

Once you learn the \texttt{dplyr} grammar there are a few additional
benefits - \texttt{dplyr} can work with other data frame ``back ends''
such as SQL databases. There is an SQL interface for relational
databases via the DBI package - \texttt{dplyr} can be integrated with
the \texttt{data.table} package for large fast tables

The \texttt{dplyr} package is handy way to both simplify and speed up
your data frame management code. It's rare that you get such a
combination at the same time!

\hypertarget{nb-ggplot2}{%
\chapter{NB: GGPlot2}\label{nb-ggplot2}}

\hypertarget{introduction-7}{%
\section{Introduction}\label{introduction-7}}

Today we'll look at GGPlot2, the graphics package associated with the
\textbf{Tidyverse}.

\hypertarget{learning-goal}{%
\section{Learning Goal}\label{learning-goal}}

You will be introduced into how and why to use \textbf{visualizations}
in DS 6001.

\begin{itemize}
\item
  Visualizations in EDA
\item
  Visualization in creating data products that communicate results, such
  as scientific publications, infographics, and interactive
  visualizations.
\end{itemize}

These things come at the end of the data science \textbf{pipeline}.

Today, I just want to introduce you to the thinking and \textbf{design
logic} behind the package, so you can be confident in learning more as
you need to.

\hypertarget{the-grammar-of-graphics}{%
\section{The Grammar of Graphics}\label{the-grammar-of-graphics}}

As with Dplyr, GGPlot2 is a an entirely new system that
\textbf{supplants} the older graph functions that are built into R.

And just as with Dplyr, it is founded on a principled analysis of its
domain and approaches code design through developing a basic
\textbf{grammar} which can then be expressed in R.

In effect, Dplyr is built on a \textbf{grammar of data} by defining a
set of \textbf{verbs} that can be used to build phrases that are put
together into larger constructs.

These verbs correspond to a \textbf{process} of data transformation.

GGPlot2 is built on a \textbf{grammar of graphics} that defines a set of
\textbf{nouns} that correspond to \textbf{the architecture of a graphic}
(aka plot).

The phrase ``grammar of graphics'' actually comes from the book by that
name written by statistician and computer scientist \textbf{Leland
Wilkinson} in 1999 and later revised:

\begin{figure}

{\centering 

\href{https://www.google.com/books/edition/The_Grammar_of_Graphics/YGgUswEACAAJ?hl=en}{\includegraphics{notebooks/M12_RViz/images/paste-39DF579F.png}}

}

\caption{The Second Edition}

\end{figure}

It's worth reading if you want to get a solid grounding in
visualization, which belongs to the \textbf{design area of data
science}.

\hypertarget{a-layered-model}{%
\section{A Layered Model}\label{a-layered-model}}

Wilkinson takes an \textbf{object-oriented approach} to visualization
and formalizes two main \textbf{principles}:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\Roman{enumi}.}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Graphics} are built out of distinct \textbf{\emph{layers}} of
  grammatical \textbf{elements.}
\item
  In each layer, meaningful \textbf{plots} are constructed through
  \textbf{mappings of data onto aesthetics.}
\end{enumerate}

The essential grammatical elements to create any visualization are:

\includegraphics{notebooks/M12_RViz/images/paste-E167991C.png}

According to Wickham, who adopted these principles and applied them to
R,

\begin{quote}
A grammar of graphics is a tool that enables us to \textbf{concisely
describe the components of a graphic}. Such a grammar allows us to
\textbf{move beyond named graphics} (e.g., the ``scatterplot'') and gain
insight into \textbf{the deep structure} that underlies statistical
graphics
(\href{https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1198/jcgs.2009.07098}{Wickham
2012}).
\end{quote}

Wickham takes this idea and develops it into this:

\includegraphics{notebooks/M12_RViz/images/paste-D2214B2A.png}

\href{https://blog.gramener.com/grammar-of-graphics-data-stories/}{Source}
(see also
\href{https://www.science-craft.com/2014/07/08/introducing-the-grammar-of-graphics-plotting-concept/}{ScienceCraft}).

You can see that everything starts with \textbf{data.}

Then data are mapped on \textbf{aesthetics} within \textbf{geometries.}

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \textbf{Geometries} are geometric things like points, lines, and bars.
\item
  \textbf{Aesthetics} are visual things like position, size, color and
  shape.
\end{itemize}

You can see how the latter are properties of the former.

Also note that aesthetics make use of visual channels to signify

\begin{itemize}
\item
  Size can means greater than, which is good for numeric scale but not
  categories
\item
  Color can signify things like value, e.g.~via
  \texttt{red\ :\ dangerous\ :\ :\ green\ :\ safe}.
\end{itemize}

These are the primary layers. The other layers apply \textbf{downstream
modifications} that add more \textbf{information} and \textbf{style} to
the graph.

\hypertarget{the-bare-minimum}{%
\section{The Bare Minimum}\label{the-bare-minimum}}

Everything starts with \texttt{ggplot()} which is part of the Tidyverse.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{library}\NormalTok{(tidyverse)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
-- Attaching packages --------------------------------------- tidyverse 1.3.2 --
v ggplot2 3.3.5     v purrr   1.0.1
v tibble  3.2.1     v dplyr   1.1.1
v tidyr   1.2.1     v stringr 1.5.0
v readr   2.1.3     v forcats 1.0.0
-- Conflicts ------------------------------------------ tidyverse_conflicts() --
x dplyr::filter() masks stats::filter()
x dplyr::lag()    masks stats::lag()
\end{verbatim}

Here is a basic graph -- a scatterplot comparing two features in the
iris dataset. I've broken out the functions and arguments so you can see
how the grammar is implemented:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{iris }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
\FunctionTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(}
  \AttributeTok{mapping =} \FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}
    \AttributeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ Sepal.Length, }
    \AttributeTok{y =}\NormalTok{ Sepal.Width)}
\NormalTok{  ) }\SpecialCharTok{+} 
  \FunctionTok{geom\_point}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{size=}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{color=}\NormalTok{Species))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{figure}[H]

{\centering \includegraphics{notebooks/M12_RViz/M12-01-GGPlot_files/figure-pdf/unnamed-chunk-4-1.pdf}

}

\end{figure}

\texttt{ggplot()} starts by creating a \textbf{coordinate system} that
you can add \textbf{layers} to.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  The \textbf{coordinate system} can be changed after the graph is
  initiated.
\end{itemize}

These \textbf{layers} are created by \textbf{geometry functions.}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  For example, \texttt{geom\_point} creates a point-based visualization.
\item
  There are many \texttt{geom\_} functions, and they can be layered on
  top of each other:

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    \texttt{geom\_point()}
  \item
    \texttt{geom\_bar()}
  \item
    \texttt{geom\_histogram()}
  \item
    \texttt{geom\_boxplot()}
  \item
    etc.
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

Here we have a plot with two layers. The second layer is created by a
\textbf{stat} function, which is similar to geom, but applies a
statistical transformation to the data.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{iris }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
\FunctionTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}
  \AttributeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ Sepal.Length, }
  \AttributeTok{y =}\NormalTok{ Sepal.Width)) }\SpecialCharTok{+} 
  \FunctionTok{geom\_point}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{size=}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{color=}\NormalTok{Species)) }\SpecialCharTok{+} 
  \FunctionTok{stat\_smooth}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{method =}\NormalTok{ lm)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
`geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
\end{verbatim}

\begin{figure}[H]

{\centering \includegraphics{notebooks/M12_RViz/M12-01-GGPlot_files/figure-pdf/unnamed-chunk-6-1.pdf}

}

\end{figure}

The core the process is that each layer \textbf{maps} \textbf{data} onto
what are called \textbf{aesthetics (\texttt{aes}).}

Aesthetics are \textbf{visual objects and properties} that can used to
represent numeric and categorical values

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  x and y positions (in a two-dimensional system)
\item
  Color
\item
  Size
\item
  Shape
\item
  Text
\end{itemize}

In addition to these elements, ggplot also provides \textbf{faceting},
which is the visual equivalent of grouping by. Just as with group by, a
data feature is used to divide the visualization into groups, each
taking the same form but showing a different subset of data.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{iris }\SpecialCharTok{\%\textgreater{}\%}
\FunctionTok{ggplot}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}
  \AttributeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ Sepal.Length, }
  \AttributeTok{y =}\NormalTok{ Sepal.Width)) }\SpecialCharTok{+} 
  \FunctionTok{geom\_point}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{size=}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{color=}\NormalTok{Species)) }\SpecialCharTok{+} 
  \FunctionTok{stat\_smooth}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{method =}\NormalTok{ lm) }\SpecialCharTok{+}
  \FunctionTok{facet\_wrap}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{facets =} \FunctionTok{vars}\NormalTok{(Species))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

`geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
\end{verbatim}

}

\begin{quote}
By the way, this is an example of Simpson's Paradox. The overall trend
is downward, but each group trend upward.
\end{quote}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]

    \AttributeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ Sepal.Length, }
    \AttributeTok{y =}\NormalTok{ Sepal.Width)) }\SpecialCharTok{+} 
    \FunctionTok{geom\_point}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{size=}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{, }\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{color=}\NormalTok{Species)) }\SpecialCharTok{+} 
    \FunctionTok{stat\_smooth}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{method =}\NormalTok{ lm) }\SpecialCharTok{+}
    \FunctionTok{stat\_smooth}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{method =}\NormalTok{ lm, }\AttributeTok{se=}\ConstantTok{FALSE}\NormalTok{, }\FunctionTok{aes}\NormalTok{(}\AttributeTok{color=}\NormalTok{Species))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

`geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
`geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

{\centering \includegraphics{notebooks/M12_RViz/M12-01-GGPlot_files/figure-pdf/unnamed-chunk-10-1.pdf}

}

\end{figure}

Anyway, the \textbf{general structure} of a ggplot statement is the
following:

\begin{verbatim}
ggplot(data = <DATA>) + 
  <GEOM_FUNCTION>(
     mapping = aes(<MAPPINGS>),
     stat = <STAT>, 
     position = <POSITION>
  ) +
  <COORDINATE_FUNCTION> +
  <FACET_FUNCTION>
\end{verbatim}

\hypertarget{the-operator}{%
\section{\texorpdfstring{The \texttt{+}
operator}{The + operator}}\label{the-operator}}

You will notice the use of the \texttt{+} operator to connect ggplot
functions together to produce a final product. Theses are not quite the
same as pipes \texttt{\%\textgreater{}\%}.

The difference is that pipes feed data from one function to another,
whereas the \texttt{+} operation combines elements to produce an
increasingly developed visualization.

Another thing to keep in mind: the \texttt{+} always goes at the
\textbf{end of a line}, not at the beginning.

Filled time series can be plotted using geom\_ribbon(). It takes two
compulsory arguments ymin and ymax.

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\# Prepare the dataframe}
\NormalTok{st\_year }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{start}\NormalTok{(AirPassengers)[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{]}
\NormalTok{st\_month }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \StringTok{"01"}
\NormalTok{st\_date }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{as.Date}\NormalTok{(}\FunctionTok{paste}\NormalTok{(st\_year, st\_month, }\StringTok{"01"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{sep=}\StringTok{"{-}"}\NormalTok{))}
\NormalTok{dates }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{seq.Date}\NormalTok{(st\_date, }\AttributeTok{length=}\FunctionTok{length}\NormalTok{(AirPassengers), }\AttributeTok{by=}\StringTok{"month"}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{df }\OtherTok{\textless{}{-}} \FunctionTok{data.frame}\NormalTok{(dates, AirPassengers, AirPassengers}\SpecialCharTok{/}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}
\FunctionTok{head}\NormalTok{(df)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\begin{verbatim}
       dates AirPassengers AirPassengers.2
1 1949-01-01           112            56.0
2 1949-02-01           118            59.0
3 1949-03-01           132            66.0
4 1949-04-01           129            64.5
5 1949-05-01           121            60.5
6 1949-06-01           135            67.5
\end{verbatim}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\CommentTok{\#\textgreater{}        dates AirPassengers AirPassengers.2}

\hypertarget{nb-r-markdown}{%
\chapter{NB: R Markdown}\label{nb-r-markdown}}

\hypertarget{introduction-8}{%
\section{Introduction}\label{introduction-8}}

R provides a notebook style coding environment similar to Jupyter.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  It follows the \textbf{literate programming} paradigm of
  \textbf{inter-leaving text and code}.
\item
  It uses a version of \href{https://www.markdownguide.org/}{Markdown}
  to create the text components.
\item
  It allows executable \textbf{code blocks}.
\item
  They can be used interactively or as \textbf{exported} documents into
  standard formats.
\end{itemize}

How, the R approach differs in some important ways:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  RMarkdown is \textbf{not visually rendered} while your are editing.

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    The document has to be `knitted' to see this.
  \item
    Newer versions of RStudio have a visual mode that does render
    Markdown, and also allows you to edit in this mode.
  \item
    This differs from Jupyter's cell-by-cell approach.
  \end{itemize}
\item
  RMarkdown \textbf{allows several programming languages} to be run in
  the same notebook. - RMarkdown files are meant to be \emph{published
  documents}, not workspaces for coding.
\item
  RMarkdown is written in markdown and uses
  \href{https://yaml.org/}{YAML}to store configuration information.

  \begin{itemize}
  \item
    Jupyter notebooks are written in \textbf{JavaScript}, which contains
    both configuration data and content data in the same structure.
  \item
    This difference is what accounts for the different editing
    experiences. JavaScript is the native programming language of web
    browsers; the notebook format is executable code that can be
    integrated into a web application.
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{varieties-of-r-markdown-outputs}{%
\section{Varieties of R Markdown
outputs}\label{varieties-of-r-markdown-outputs}}

R Markdown is designed to be output to several formats:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{R Notebooks}

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Designed to previewed
  \item
    Or output to \texttt{(html\textbar{}pdf\textbar{}doc)\_notebook}
  \item
    Have Preview in RStudio toolbar (but also Knit in menu)
  \end{itemize}
\item
  \textbf{Documents}

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Output to \texttt{(html\textbar{}pdf\textbar{}doc)\_document}
  \item
    Has Knit in RStudio toolbar
  \end{itemize}
\item
  \textbf{Presentations}

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Produce slideshows from your source file, in ioslides, beamer, or
    powerpoint.
  \end{itemize}
\item
  \textbf{Shiny}

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Create interactive apps that can be published on the web.
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{knitting}{%
\section{Knitting}\label{knitting}}

Knitting is the process of compiling all the code and visual assets of
an RMarkdown into a single file.

\hypertarget{publishing}{%
\section{Publishing}\label{publishing}}

RMarkdown has publication in mind as an outcome. RStudio allows you to
publish in these destinations:

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \href{https://rpubs.com/}{RPubs}
\item
  \href{https://www.rstudio.com/products/connect/}{R Studio Connect}
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{outputting}{%
\section{Outputting}\label{outputting}}

There are two ways to set the output of a document:

\begin{enumerate}
\def\labelenumi{\arabic{enumi}.}
\item
  Permanently, by modifying the YAML header:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{title}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }\StringTok{"Viridis Demo"}
\FunctionTok{output}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ html\_document}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
\item
  Transiently, by calling \texttt{rmarkdown::render()} by hand:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{rmarkdown}\SpecialCharTok{::}\FunctionTok{render}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"diamond{-}sizes.Rmd"}\NormalTok{, }\AttributeTok{output\_format =} \StringTok{"word\_document"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

  This is useful if you want to programmatically produce multiple types
  of output.
\end{enumerate}

RStudio's knit button renders a file to the first format listed in its
\texttt{output} field.

You can also do it by code:

\begin{verbatim}
knitr::include_graphics("screenshots/rmarkdown-knit.png")
\end{verbatim}

Each output format is associated with an R function.

You can either write \texttt{foo} or \texttt{pkg::foo}.

If you omit \texttt{pkg}, the default is assumed to be rmarkdown.

It's important to know the name of the function that makes the output
because that's where you get help.

For example, to figure out what parameters you can set with
\texttt{html\_document}, look at \texttt{?rmarkdown::html\_document}.

\hypertarget{output-options}{%
\subsection{Output options}\label{output-options}}

To override the default parameter values, you need to use an expanded
\texttt{output} field. For example, if you wanted to render an
\texttt{html\_document} with a floating table of contents, you'd use:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{output}\KeywordTok{:}
\AttributeTok{  }\FunctionTok{html\_document}\KeywordTok{:}
\AttributeTok{    }\FunctionTok{toc}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }\CharTok{true}
\AttributeTok{    }\FunctionTok{toc\_float}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }\CharTok{true}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

You can even render to multiple outputs by supplying a list of formats:

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\FunctionTok{output}\KeywordTok{:}
\AttributeTok{  }\FunctionTok{html\_document}\KeywordTok{:}
\AttributeTok{    }\FunctionTok{toc}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }\CharTok{true}
\AttributeTok{    }\FunctionTok{toc\_float}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ }\CharTok{true}
\AttributeTok{  }\FunctionTok{pdf\_document}\KeywordTok{:}\AttributeTok{ default}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

Note the special syntax if you don't want to override any of the default
options.
